<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Assess     02-20 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Assess,0749</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Will Be Focus Of Shultz Mission</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Analysis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Saturday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz will have
to overcome Yitzhak Shamir's growing opposition if he expects the
new U.S. peace proposals to get anywhere.
   The 72-year-old prime minister, a former underground fighter and
senior spymaster, has a reputation for being tough-minded. Aides
say he will not yield to the pressure of negative publicity or
diplomatic arm-twisting.
   Shamir has expressed serious reservations, and some annoyance,
about American ideas for reviving progress toward peace in the
Middle East. To clear the air in advance of the Shultz visit next
week, he sent emissaries to Washington to declare what he would and
would not accept.
   One envoy was Ehud Olmert, a senior figure in Shamir's
conservative Likud Bloc, who said he told Shultz the prime minister
would not agree to territorial compromise in advance of peace talks.
   ``Territory for peace is a non-starter,'' Olmert said in an
interview. ``We are ready to negotiate on the territorial issue,
but that doesn't mean we are ready to accept withdrawing from the
territories before negotiations.''
   Israel has occupied the West Bank and Gaza Strip since capturing
them from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Shultz suggested the land-for-peace formula in a speech to the
Council on Foreign Relations in Washington and it apparently upset
Shamir.
   ``The timing, manner and phrasing was inappropriate, inasmuch as
he wants to have the prime minister in the process,'' Olmert said,
adding that he believed the secretary of state realized his
``mistake.''
   Shultz's plan calls for:
   _ An international forum that would convene by April to launch
Arab-Israeli negotiations. The Soviets would likely play an equal
role with Washington.
   _ An interim solution for the West Bank and Gaza in the form of
self-rule for the 1.5 million Palestinians who live there.
Elections would be held by October to choose a self-governing body.
   _ Talks on the final status of the occupied lands to start by
December even without progress on autonomy.
   Shamir initially indicated flexibility, to encourage
negotiations, but the suggestion that he would agree to yield some
of the occupied land caused a storm of protest among Likud
hard-liners.
   Perhaps fearing concessions would be seen as giving in to Arab
rioters, Shamir has drawn back, with tougher rhetoric and warnings
between the lines that he will not accept pressure from the
Americans.
   He has been cool to Soviet involvement, requested a clearer
definition of the forum that would launch negotiations, and
expressed opposition to linking talks on a temporary solution in
the occupied territories with negotiations on a permanent
settlement.
   He argues that several years of experience with limited
self-rule is needed to build confidence for a stable solution.
   ``There is a need for a considerable period of practical
experience, of coexistence between us and the Palestinian Arab
authorities before the question of sovereignty can be approached,''
Shamir said in a speech this week.
   Shultz will begin a Middle East shuttle Thursday after a visit
to Moscow, using Jerusalem as a base and traveling to Jordan, Egypt
and possibly other Arab countries, Israeli officials said.
   His most intensive shuttle, however, may be between Shamir and
Foreign Minister Shimon Peres. The two partners and rivals in
Israel's coalition government and who disagree sharply on strategy
for peace.
   ``They are miles apart,'' an official close to Peres said
privately. ``Shultz will try to bring them to together as he has in
the past.''
   Peres, leader of the center-left Labor Party, has endorsed
Jordan's proposal for an international conference, which Shamir
says would be biased against Israel. Labor accepts the
land-for-peace formula but the Likud fears giving up land would
make Israel vulnerable.
   Aides to both leaders say Shultz will concentrate on winning
Shamir's agreement, since Peres already has accepted the Shultz
plan. ``Shultz's major goal is to convince Shamir,'' one official
said.
   A senior aide to Shamir, also speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the prime minister views the Shultz visit ``with
caution'' but is ready to listen and give his position. ``Some of
his (Shultz's) ideas are okay and others are not,'' the aide said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Nicolas B. Tatro is chief of The Associated
Press bureau in Jerusalem.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
