<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Panama Bjt   02-20 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Panama, Bjt,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panama Indicates Interest in Deal on Noriega</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama, apparently seeking a way out of a
legal and diplomatic predicament with the United States, made
discreet inquiries about U.S. willingness to drop federal charges
against military strong man Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega,
administration officials say.
   The State Department confirmed Friday that Panamanian
authorities had asked about that possibility and that Assistant
Secretary of State Elliott Abrams raised the matter with the
Justice Department.
   After being told that dropping the charges was ``technically
possible,'' Abrams relayed that message Wednesday to Panamanian
President Eric Arturo Delvalle during an unannounced meeting in
Miami.
   But during their discussion, Abrams ``made no deal, offered no
deal and was not in a position to offer a deal,'' State Department
spokesman Charles Redman said.
   Redman added that the indictments against Noriega are
``obviously based on strong evidence, and we have every intention
on carrying through with them.''
   The Panamanian Embassy had no comment on the Miami meeting,
saying only that Delvalle had gone to Miami for medical treatment.
   Redman denied an account in The New York Times that said Abrams
told Delvalle the indictment might be dropped if Noriega withdrew
from politics and went into exile. The Times cited as its sources
U.S. officials and congressional staff members it did not name.
   The Panamanian inquiry was made as a political crisis grew in
Panama, brought on in part by Noriega's legal problems.
   Indictments handed down in Florida two weeks ago portrayed
Noriega as a key member of an international drug trafficking
conspiracy.
   Among other activities, he was accused of providing protection
and other government services to international drug smugglers who
shipped cocaine and marijuana to the United States through Panama.
   U.S.-Panamanian agreements do not provide for his extradition,
making it virtually impossible for Noriega to be brought to trial.
   At the same time, the Reagan administration is deeply concerned
about Panama's political stability and has been encouraging Noriega
and his military allies to withdraw from politics.
   The administration believes that the security of the Panama
Canal is best assured through elected civilian rule. Delvalle is
widely viewed as a figurehead president who bows to Noriega's
wishes.
   The Times account said that under the formula Abrams discussed,
Noriega could move to any country he wished without having to
concern himself with the possibility of extradition to the United
States.
   With Noriega living in exile, this scenario also could enhance
the possibility _ consistent with U.S. objectives _ of an evolution
to a civilian-led government in Panama.
   But Redman insisted that the administration has no interest in
any arrangement for Noriega to be exiled in exchange for a drop of
the charges.
   ``We all see the drug problem of tremendous importance in the
United States as well as throughout the hemisphere,'' Redman said,
reaffirming that the indictments will not be withdrawn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
