<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Germany     02-20 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Germany,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kohl, Reagan Reaffirm United Strategy Against Soviets</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan and West German Chancellor
Helmut Kohl are lauding a Western effort to build a common arms
control strategy so NATO can manage the Soviets with ``realism,
strength and alliance unity.''
   The two leaders ended talks at the White House on Friday with a
pledge to intensify the effort at a NATO summit March 2-3.
   ``What we need now is an overall concept covering the whole
field of disarmament, and there I do not see any difference between
us and the Americans,'' Kohl told reporters before heading back to
Bonn.
   ``We agreed that we must deal with the Soviet Union from a
position of realism, strength and alliance unity,''
   Since reaching agreement with the Soviets to eliminate
land-based nuclear missiles with ranges between 300 miles and 3,125
miles, the United States and its allies have been trying to set
goals for further talks with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and
his aides.
   ``We want to get out of a situation where we merely react to
proposals which have been submitted by Gorbachev. We want to put
down proposals and let him react to them,'' Kohl said.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz, who attended the White
House meeting, left later in the day for another round of
negotiations with the Soviets in Moscow. Kohl said Shultz pledged
to convey to the Soviets the West German concern about ethnic
Germans facing discrimination in Soviet bloc countries.
   NATO already has agreed on a first priority of a U.S.-Soviet
reduction in long-range missiles and bombers, while seeking cuts in
conventional and chemical weapons.
   ``We were in agreement that all these disarmament questions and
issues as well as the necessary measures to preserve our common
security should be combined in form and overall concept for our
alliance,'' Kohl said.
   Each of the 16 allies, depending on its politics and geography,
has different interests to advance, and one of the key differences
was reflected in comments after Kohl's meeting with Reagan.
   West Germany is particularly eager for negotiations to reduce
tactical nuclear weapons _ those with ranges below 300 miles _ and
wants those talks included in any conferences that deal with
conventional weapons. Kohl, whose country would be threatened by
such weapons if a war broke out in Europe, reiterated the desire
for quick and comprehensive talks on the short-range systems.
   The United States, which believes tactical nuclear weapons are
necessary to deter a conventional attack, wants to defer
negotiations to reduce the short-range systems. Indeed, it is
working on plans to modernize these weapons, with NATO approval.
   During Kohl's visit, the two sides sought to minimize the
importance of the disagreement. Kohl said he did not favor the
elimination of the tactical nuclear weapons: artillery shells and
short-range missiles.
   He does not seek a ``denuclearized zone, least of all in
Europe,'' Kohl said.
   Kohl was asked at the news conference about concerns that
modernization of short-range weapons would touch off protests like
those that rocked Europe in the early 1980s after NATO decided to
deploy intermediate-range weapons.
   ``I don't share that fear,'' Kohl said.
   In its efforts to play down the issue, the Reagan administration
noted during Kohl's visit that further study is needed before the
most powerful of the short-range systems _ a missile to replace the
75-mile-range Lance _ is deployed and it may not go into operation
before 1995.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
