<1ST_LINE>r w PM-GlassMerger     02-20 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Glass Merger,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Keeps Glass Merger on Hold</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposed merger between two of the nation's
largest manufacturers of glass containers remains on hold today in
the wake of a ruling by a federal appeals court.
   Late Friday afternoon, the U.S. Court of Appeals issued an
administrative stay of a lower court decision that would have
cleared the way for the merger between Owens-Illinois Inc. and
Brockway Inc.
   Earlier in the day, the Federal Trade Commission had asked the
appeals court to extend until next Tuesday a restraining order
blocking the merger until the agency could decide whether to appeal
a ruling by U.S. District Court Judge Joyce Hens Green.
   On Thursday, Green refused the FTC's request for a preliminary
injunction, ruling that the FTC had not proven the deal would harm
competition.
   FTC spokeswoman Susan Tichnor said the agency will have until
next Tuesday to file an appeal and that the court will issue a
decision sometime after Owens-Illinois files a response Wednesday.
   Attorneys for Owens-Illinois said there is no excuse for the
FTC's ``unusual filing'' Friday to keep the merger on hold until
the agency can decide whether to appeal.
   ``The FTC has been acutely aware since the beginning of this
case of the extreme time sensitivity surrounding the merger and, in
that regard, has had ample time to prepare for the possibility of a
decision adverse to it,'' said Paul Warnke, an attorney for
Owens-Illinois.
   Last September, the Toledo, Ohio-based Owens-Illinois proposed
to buy Brockway, of Jacksonville, Fla., for $750 million, or $60
per share.
   The merger would make the combined company the largest
manufacturer of glass containers in the industry. The nation's top
manufacturer is Anchor Glass Container Corp., which controls 23.7
percent of the market.
   The FTC has said the merger might violate federal antitrust laws
by substantially reducing competition in the glass container
industry and creating conditions for price discrimination. It wants
to halt the merger until it can conduct an administrative review of
the proposal.
   But Green accepted the argument advanced by the two
manufacturers that competition from the plastics and
metal-packaging industry will hold down prices.
</TEXT>
