<FILEID>AP-NR-02-20-88 0251EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Stroke-World     02-20 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stroke-World,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Siberia Is World's Stroke Capital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Siberia is the stroke capital of the world, and
heavy drinking and cold weather could be partly to blame,
researchers say.
   Soviet stroke data, gathered as part of a World Health
Organization program, were released for the first time Friday at a
stroke conference sponsored by the American Heart Association.
   ``We were surprised,'' said Dr. Kjell Asplund. ``We thought that
China and Japan would be the higest.''
   The study showed that Canada and Denmark are the safest places
to live, at least as far as stroke is concerned, although the
stroke rate is low throughout most of North America, southern
Europe and Australia.
   Asplund, a researcher at Umea University in Umea, Sweden, said
the data suggest that strokes must have several causes. While
racial differences may play a role, they don't explain all of the
variations in the risk of stroke around the world.
   The study found that in Siberia, the stroke rate was 119 for
every 100,000 men and 107 for every 100,000 women. These figures
were the highest in the world and significantly ahead of China, the
country with the second highest stroke rate.
   Strokes are also common in Japan, but data collected there were
so sparse they were not included in the analysis.
   Strokes among men are least common in Canada, where they strike
21 in 100,000. In women they are least frequent in Denmark, where
they occur in 8 in 100,000.
   Asked why strokes are so common in Siberia, Asplund said, ``At
this point, we can only guess. We know that alcohol consumption is
very high. High alcohol use among men is associated with a high
risk for stroke. I also suspect that there are some climate factors
involved.''
   Although there are exceptions, such as Canada, he said it
appears that strokes are more common in cold climates than in
milder places. He noted that people are more likely to suffer
strokes in northern Sweden than in southern Sweden and in Scotland
than in England.
   Some experts suspect that Asians are more likely to suffer
strokes, at least in part, because of racial differences. However,
Asplund said that most people in Siberia moved there from European
parts of the Soviet Union.
   ``It's not only a racial thing,'' he said. ``It must have other
determinants as well. The goal of this study is to find the
determinants of the huge variations in stroke around the world.''
   He said the researchers will be trying to learn why the stroke
rate is falling rapidly in the United States, while it is stable or
increasing in many other countries.
   The study found that in most places, strokes are more common in
men than in women. The only exceptions to this were Sweden, Canada
and Israel, where strokes are slightly more common among women.
   The 10-year project, called Monitoring of Trends and
Determinants of Cardiovascular Disease, or MONICA, is being
conducted in 26 countries and will conclude in 1994.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880220-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-20-88 0254EST</FILEID>
