<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Brain-DeadBaby     02-20 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brain-Dead Baby,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Hospitals Reject Brain-Dead Baby's Liver</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOMA LINDA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three hospitals turned down the liver
of a brain-dead baby whose body was being maintained on
life-support systems to preserve his organs for transplant,
officials said Friday.
   Baby John, who was born Tuesday with most of his brain missing,
a condition known as anencephaly, was pronounced brain dead
Thursday at Loma Linda University Medical Center.
   No other cases in which anencephalics have been kept on
life-support for organ transplant have been announced in the United
States, although Dr. Leonard Bailey, chief of Loma Linda's heart
transplant program, last year suggested there have been such
infants.
   Doctors plan to maintain the body on life support for up to
seven days in hope of finding recipients for its organs, hospital
spokeswoman Anita Rockwell said.
   One liver transplant candidate in Pittsburgh was not an
appropriate match and another in that city became infected,
delaying any transplant, Ms. Rockwell said.
   A medical center in Wisconsin also was unable to accept the
liver for another candidate because it had committed itself to do
another transplant and could not perform two in one day, Ms.
Rockwell said.
   UCLA Medical Center in Los Angeles turned rejected the liver as
not an ideal candidate for their recipient, Ms. Rockwell said.
   Anencephaly usually is fatal within days after birth. An
anencephalic infant's organs can be transplanted only if organ
damage is prevented by maintaining the infant on life-support from
birth.
</TEXT>
