<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy-metal rock group Motley Crue warned
fans not to imitate its show stunts after a 12-year-old boy set his
blue jeans on fire while trying to copy the group's ``human torch''
video act.
   Bryan Tucker, who had burns over 10 percent of his body, was
reported in good condition today at Memorial Hospital after he
poured rubbing alcohol on his jeans and torched them. He put the
flames out in a filled bathtub.
   ``Various of Motley Crue's show stunts require special
equipment, clothing and other materials ... and should not be
attempted at home,'' said the statement released Thursday by
management firm McGhee Entertainment Inc. in Los Angeles.
   Bryan's mother, Wendy Tucker, said he was in great pain but that
Motley Crue was not to blame for her son's experiment at their home
Wednesday.
   ``In my day, my mom would not let me watch Superman, because he
jumped out of buildings,'' she said. ``It's just a different time.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Kirk Douglas, a veteran of more than 70
movies, was honored for his life's work at the Berlin Film
Festival, Europe's second-largest annual movie event.
   The 71-year-old actor received the honorary Golden Camera award
Thursday in an invitation-only ceremony attended by about 500
guests.
   ``This evening, I am really very happy,'' said Douglas, speaking
in German. ``I have made three films in Germany, and so have had
the opportunity to learn a little German.''
   Douglas' wife, Anne, also attended the ceremony.
   The Berlin Film Festival is Europe's second-biggest annual movie
event after the more prestigious festival in Cannes, France.
