<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dino de Laurentiis, whose film company has
been battered by a string of box-office flops, has stepped down as
chairman and chief executive of De Laurentiis Entertainment Group.
   The 68-year-old de Laurentiis, who was a successful filmmaker in
his native Italy, also gave proxy to the company's board Friday to
vote his stock. He owns 60 percent of the Los Angeles company he
founded in May 1986.
   For the nine months ended Nov. 30, the company posted losses of
$36.2 million on revenues of $46 million.
   The most recent results included $27 million in writedowns on
four films that flopped at the box office _ ``Near Dark,''
``Weeds,'' ``Hiding Out'' and ``Date With an Angel'' _ and on a
fifth, ``Total Recall,'' on which work was suspended.
   Stephen Greenwald, the company's president, was elected to take
de Laurentiis' posts.
