<2ND_LINE>AM-North-Moon,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Linked to Unification Church Lobbies for North Pardon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nationwide lobbying campaign seeking a
pardon for Lt. Col. Oliver North for his involvement in the
Iran-Contra affair has been launched by a conservative group that
is working with activists from the Rev. Sun Myung Moon's
Unification Church, The Washington Post reported Saturday.
   ``We think North is a hero and he ought to be treated as such,''
said Robert Grant, chairman of the lobbying group Christian Voice
and president of the new American Freedom Coalition.
   The coalition has extensive links to Moon's Unification Church
movement, according to the newspaper. It said Bo Hi Pak, Moon's top
deputy and president of The Washington Times, which is owned by
Moon, was instrumental in founding the group and Phillip Sanchez,
one of Pak's chief political aides and president of Causa USA, is a
member of the coalition's national policy board.
   Grant said Causa has given the coalition a network of activists
throughout the United States _ most of whom are Unification Church
members _ to help build local support.
   However, the coalition's literature never mentions the
Unification Church and Pak's name is not included on the group's
five-member board of directors, the Post said.
   The coalition, chaired by former Reps. Richard Ichord, D-Mo.,
and Bob Wilson, R-Calif., recently sent more than a million letters
asking recipients to sign a ``Pardon Colonel North'' petition to
President Reagan.
   North is a target of the Iran-Contra investigation being
conducted by independent counsel Lawrence Walsh but has not been
indicted.
</TEXT>
