<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BombExpert     02-20 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bomb Expert,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Bomb Expert Wraps Up 43-year Career With One Last Blast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAEN, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marcel Piattier cleared Omaha Beach of
German mines the day after the Allies stormed it on D-Day, and went
on to make a career out of defusing or detonating unexploded World
War II bombs.
   On Friday, The 66-year-old Piattier retired with a bang, safely
exploding a 300-pound English bomb found in January in this town
150 miles north of Paris.
   The live bomb couldn't be moved and was detonated near the
center of town, causing no damage.
   In his last year as head of the regional bomb and mine clearing
service, the man considered the dean of the 25 civil defense
explosive experts in France was kept busy.
   ``In the second half of 1987, we received 560 calls to
neutralize bombs found by individuals,'' Piattier said.
   He says his work in his later years was safer than it used to be.
   ``In 1945, we probed mine fields with bayonettes,'' he recalled.
``In two years, 27 French mine clearers died, and that's not
counting the German prisoners of war we used.''
   To determine if the bomb detonated Friday was still live,
Piattier used sophisticated X-ray equipment, similar to that used
at nuclear power plants, to see inside to the strike-pin.
   Normandy was the scene of the Allied invasion in 1944 and saw
intense fighting that left behind thousands of bombs and mines that
often turn up unexpectedly. In the past year, bombs have been found
by workers digging the English Channel tunnel and near a hospital
in Caen.
   The most dangerous explosives still scattered throughout the
verdant countryside are small anti-personnel bombs dropped in
bunches from German planes.
   ``A woman had her leg torn away in June and a child died in
September from these bombs,'' said Piattier, who added that he has
found ``several thousand'' bombs and mines in four decades of work.
   Piattier's first task was clearing the German mines from Omaha
Beach the day after U.S. forces landed on June 6, 1944.
   ``I was the first French soldier on the beach and even before
the second soldier arrived I had found hundreds and hundreds of
mines,'' he said.
   Piattier was lucky to reach retirement. In the past two years,
six of his colleagues have died in the line of duty, he said.
   ``My wife is happy. She thinks I'll be safe now at home, but I'm
not so sure,'' he said. ``I'd like to stay in contact with the
service and help out when I can.''
</TEXT>
