<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Theater-Carrie     02-20 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Theater-Carrie,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Broadway-Bound Musical Gets Wan Reviews</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Carrie,'' the $7 million Broadway-bound musical
based on the Stephen King novel, received tepid reviews following
its premiere at the Royal Shakespeare Theater in
Stratford-upon-Avon.
   Jack Tinker in the Daily Mail called the show, scheduled to open
April 27 at New York's Virginia Theater, ``an expensive mess.''
   But he praised 17-year-old newcomer Linzi Hateley as the
telekinetic Carrie of the title, a traumatized adolescent played by
Sissy Spacek in the 1976 film version of the book.
   ``I hope sincerely that Broadway takes Miss Hateley to its
heart. It can take the rest wherever it pleases,'' Tinker wrote of
Thursday's performance.
   Milton Shulman in The Standard thought the show, presented in
association with the Royal Shakespeare Company, lacked ``that
element of supernatural awe'' that made the movie memorable.
   He added: ``If `Carrie' has to be transformed into a musical,
(director) Terry Hands has probably done it as well as it can be
done. But one has to ask whether the idea and the production were
really necessary.''
   Originally mooted for Broadway several years back, the show is
now headed for New York in a cast made up equally of Britons and
Americans under a special arrangement with the actors' union,
Equity.
   The behind-the-scenes talent is of mixed nationality, as well.
Choreographer Debbie Allen, composer Michael Gore and lyricist Dean
Pitchford are all American. Director Hands and his design team _
Ralph Koltai and Alexander Reid _ are British.
   Michael Coveney in The Financial Times said the musical was
``enjoyable in a masochistic way,'' but lamented Hands'
participation in ``an utter cultural vacuum of dance studio
robotics with a hint of cultural and classical pretensions.''
   Coveney and the other critics all had kind words for Broadway
veteran Barbara Cook, who plays Carrie's mother Margaret, the
religious fanatic played on-screen by Piper Laurie.
   Coveney said the 60-year-old Miss Cook was ``superb,'' and
Tinker called her ``Broadway's reclaimed heroine.''
   Irving Wardle in The Times of London said the voices of Linzi
Hateley and Barbara Cook provided ``the most thrilling sounds of
the evening.''
   ``Carrie'' is the second mother-daughter musical to open
back-to-back locally. Wednesday night saw the London debut at the
Cambridge Theater of ``The Rink,'' the 1984 Broadway flop that
starred Chita Rivera and Liza Minnelli.
   The London bow received mixed marks for the material _ a maudlin
reconciliation drama set in an abandoned roller skating rink _ but
praise for the two leads: Josephine Blake and Diane Langton.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
