<FILEID>AP-NR-02-20-88 0119EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Cyprus-Elections Bjt   02-20 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cyprus-Elections, Bjt,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Refuses to Back Candidates In Sunday Runoff Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Spyros Kyprianou refused to
back either presidential candidate in Sunday's runoff elections
after he lost a bid for a third term, throwing wide open Cyprus'
most hotly contested vote.
   Kyprianou's centrist Democratic Party, Diko, said Friday that it
did not agree with the stands of either Glafcos Clerides, leader of
the right-wing Democratic Rally Party, or millionaire businessman
George Vassiliou, an independent backed by the powerful Communist
Party, Akel.
   That left Kyprianou's 91,000 supporters free to vote either way.
   Diko's surprise move came after days of backroom bargaining.
Rivals were eliminated in a first-round ballot last Sunday.
   Kyprianou's third-place showing last Sunday took him out of the
race.
   The small socialist party, Edek, announced it was putting the
9.4 percent of the vote it won Sunday behind Vassiliou in a leftist
alliance.
   On paper, that guarantees Vassiliou just under 40 percent of the
vote when this Mediterranean island's 363,000-strong Greek Cypriot
electorate votes. Vassilou gathered 30.11 percent of last Sunday's
vote.
   The conservative, pro-Western Clerides, 68, a veteran political
warhorse, topped Sunday's poll with 33.32 percent. But he will have
to secure at least two-thirds of the votes Kyprianou won to edge
ahead of Vassiliou this Sunday.
   The election has developed into a straight left-right battle.
For the first time in a Cypriot presidential contest since
independence from Britain in 1960, the outcome cannot be predicted.
   Political analysts believe the Diko vote will split roughly down
the middle, with just a slight swing toward Clerides. That may not
be enough to ensure him victory.
   The election has been dominated by the partition issue.
   Cyprus has been divided since the Turkish army invaded in July
1974 after a short-lived coup by militant Greek Cypriot supporters
of union with Greece.
   The Turks overran the northern third of the island. The Turkish
Cypriot minority declared a breakaway republic in 1983.
   Clerides has pledged that if elected, he will form an all-party
government of national unity to revive deadlocked negotiations
between Cyprus' Greek and Turkish communities to reunite the island.
   Seeking to strengthen his national unity strategy, Clerides
announced in a television debate Thursday night that he was
resigning as leader of Democratic Rally to head into Sunday's
showdown poll as an independent.
   Vassiliou dismissed that as an electoral ploy and pointed out
that the other three parties have rejected Clerides' coalition
proposal as unfeasible.
   Clerides and Vassiliou, 56, earlier concentrated in knocking
Kyprianou out of the race and blocking his election for a third
five-year term. With Kyprianou out of the way, they are now
slamming each other.
   Clerides is accused of being a ``right-wing, anti-labor
reactionary'' who heads a party that harbors the extremists who
were behind the ill-starred 1974 coup that briefly ousted Cyprus'
first president, the late Archbishop Makarios.
   Clerides rejects the charge and accuses Vassiliou, a self-made
millionaire making his first foray into politics, of being a
communist pawn.
   Both men, however, support the unconditional resumption of
negotiations with the Turkish side.
   Kyprianou had insisted that talks should resume only after the
withdrawal of the 35,000 Turkish troops and 65,000 settlers shipped
to northern Cyprus from the Turkish mainland.
   Clerides and Vassiliou also demand a Turkish withdrawal, but do
not make this a precondition for talks that have been stalled for
the last three years.
   Taverns and most restaurants will remain closed from noon today
until noon Monday in compliance with a law banning sale of alcohol
at election time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
