<2ND_LINE>AM-Jersey Crash, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0433,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Commuter Plane Carrying Six Crashes in New Jersey</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts lead to clarify that there were no survivors; INSERTS
1 graf after 3rd graf to ADD quote from Willett.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HAMILTON TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small plane crashed in dense
fog and driving rain Friday night in a wooded area near Atlantic
City, killing at least six people, officials said. There were no
survivors.
   The twin-engine Piper Najavo en route from Norwood, Mass., to
Pomona went down about sometime after 10:10 p.m., when its radar
signal was lost, said Anthony Willett, a Federal Aviation
Administration spokesman.
   Willett said at least six people were killed. It was not
immediately known how many people were aboard the plane, which went
down about two miles from Atlantic City Airport, he said.
   ``I don't have a passenger manifest in front of me, so I can't
be sure,'' he said. ``It's pouring rain down here, the plane is in
the woods, it's just hard to be sure.''
   Willett said that the plane, 32 feet long with a 40-foot wing
span, is of a type commonly used by commuter airlines, but that the
aircraft may have been privately owned.
   The hour-long search for the wreckage was hampered by fog and
rain, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
