<DOCNO> AP880220-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-20-88 0353EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Brain-DeadBaby     02-20 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brain-Dead Baby,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hospital Having Difficulty Donating Brain-Dead Baby's Liver</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOMA LINDA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three hospitals have turned down the
liver of a brain-dead baby whose body was being maintained on
life-support machines today, and tests indicated the organ was
failing, a hospital spokeswoman said.
   The 7-pound infant known as Baby John was born Tuesday with most
of its brain missing, and was pronounced dead two days later at
Loma Linda University Medical Center.
   The baby was the first brain-absent infant in the nation to be
placed on artificial life support to keep its organs healthy for
transplant, hospital officials said. Doctors had planned to
maintain the body for up to seven days, but a blood test Friday
``suggests that his liver is failing,'' hospital spokeswoman Anita
Rockwell said.
   One prospective candidate in Pittsburgh was not an appropriate
match and another in the same hospital became infected, delaying
any possible transplant, she said Friday.
   A medical center in Wisconsin also was unable to accept the
liver for another candidate because they were committed to another
transplant and could not do two in one day, Ms. Rockwell said.
   ``The doctors in Wisconsin have refused the liver pending
further studies,'' the spokeswoman said.
   UCLA Medical Center in Los Angeles turned down the liver because
they feel it is not an ideal candidate for their recipient, Ms.
Rockwell said.
   Baby John was born with only a brain stem, a condition known as
anencephaly that usually is fatal within days of birth. An infant's
healthy organs can be transplanted only if organ damage is
prevented by maintaining the infant on life support from birth.
   Loma Linda is the nation's only medical center to experiment
with using anencephalics as organ donors.
</TEXT>
