<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Force Hoping To Hang On To Its Pilots Longer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force, concerned that it's losing too
many pilots to higher-paying commercial airlines, is considering a
bonus program to encourage its aviators to stick with the military.
   Air Force Secretary Edward C. Aldridge said Friday that while
the details haven't been worked out, ``basically we would pay
pilots something on the order of $9,000 to $12,000 per year for
signing up for a period of time as bonuses to the basic pay that
they would have.''
   The $54 million bonus program is needed because stepped-up
hiring by commercial airlines has caused the re-enlistment rate for
military pilots to drop steadily, Aldridge said at a news
conference.
   Whatever the Air Force recommends still would have to be
approved by Congress.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Commuter Aircraft Travel Expected To See Rapid Growth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's latest aviation forecast
predicts that passenger travel via commuter aircraft will increase
sharply in the coming years, outpacing growth in travel on
commercial jetliners.
   In a forecast released Friday, the Federal Aviation
Administration said commuter planes are expected to carry 58
million people annually by 1999, up from 27 million people last
year.
   The number of people flying commercial jetliners is expected to
grow from about 445 million passengers in 1987 to nearly 765
million in 1999.
   The FAA forecast said air traffic controllers will be handling a
third more planes in 1999 than they do now.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Petition Seeks Halt To Government Security Forms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An organization that represents foreign
service officers is asking a federal judge to halt the government's
practice of making some employees sign agreements not to disclose
classified information.
   The American Foreign Service Association filed a motion Friday
in U.S. District Court for a preliminary injunction to force
Secretary of State George Shultz to stop ordering State Department
employees to sign the non-disclosure forms.
   The injunction also would direct CIA Director William Webster
and Steven Garfinkel, head of the Information Security Oversight
Office, to order other federal agencies to stop forcing employees
to sign the forms.
   Critics in Congress contend the forms violate the First
Amendment rights of government employees.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Justice Says It Will Stay Out Of Further Shuttle Settlement Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department says it won't join in
negotiating any additional settlements for the families of the
astronauts killed in the Challenger shuttle crash.
   The department, which negotiated settlements with four of the
seven families in December 1986, feels it would be unfair to
contribute to any settlements higher than those agreed to in 1986
and that the government has no legal liability in the accident,
department spokeswoman Amelia Brown said Friday.
   Last week, the father and brother of mission specialist Judith
A. Resnik signed an agreement with shuttle contractor Morton
Thiokol Inc. for payment of from $1.5 million to $2.5 million. The
Justice Department declined to participate in the negotiations
leading to that settlement.
   Resnik's relatives weren't involved in the 1986 settlement.
</TEXT>
