<FILEID>AP-NR-02-20-88 0357EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Afghanistan     02-20 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pakistani Envoy Warns Of Afghan Bloodbath</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Soviet troops withdraw from Afghanistan before
there is an interim coalition government in place, rival Afghan
factions could become embroiled in unending civil strife,
Pakistan's acting foreign minister warned.
   ``In our opinion, the way things are being worked out by the
Soviets, it is going to lead to a bloodbath,'' the diplomat, Zain
Noorani, told a news conference in London Friday.
   He said hundreds of thousands of Afghans could be killed if a
political settlement does not precede a Soviet departure, and
called on the West to press Moscow for an agreement on an interim
government.
   President Mohammad Zia Ul-Haq's government in Islamabad wants a
transition government in Kabul, the Afghan capital, before it will
sign an agreement leading to Soviet withdrawal and the return home
of more than two million Afghan refugees now living in Pakistan.
   Noorani said that without an interim coalition government,
Islamabad believes the refugees will not return to Afghanistan.
   ``We anticipate that under such circumstances more refugees will
be coming into Pakistan from Afghanistan,'' he said.
   Noorani, who met with Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe
earlier Friday, denied Pakistan was trying to sabotage the chances
of an agreement at talks in Geneva between Pakistan and Afghanistan
on how to end the conflict.
   He said Islamabad wants Soviet forces to leave, but also wants a
lasting settlement.
   Noorani said Afghan guerrilla leaders and refugee and emigre
representatives on Monday would propose what he called a detailed
framework of a coalition government.
   Earlier this month, Mikhail S. Gorbachev offered to begin
withdrawing the estimated 115,000 Soviet troops in Afghanistan on
May 15 if Pakistan signs an accord at the next session of the
U.N.-sponsored peace talks in Geneva that begin March 2.
   But Gorbachev also said the Soviets would not attempt to
influence the composition of the Kabul government after they leave.
   The Soviet leader said all Soviet forces could be withdrawn in
10 months if agreement is reached at Geneva. The Soviets later
accused Pakistan of trying to block chances of an agreement.
   Pakistan's stand has some backing in Washington and London, but
Western leaders have urged Islamabad not to go so far as to
jeopardize Gorbachev's withdrawal pledge.
   Soviet forces entered Afghanistan in December 1979 and replaced
one pro-Soviet government in Kabul with another. The Soviet move
was condemned by the United States, Britain and other Western
governments.
   The Soviets and Afghan government soldiers have been fighting
Moslem guerrillas trying to overthrow the Kabul government.
   The guerrilla groups maintain bases in Pakistan and have
received support from the United States, Iran and Pakistan.
   The British Foreign Office said in a statement Friday following
Noorani's meeting with Howe: ``There is a tremendous amount of
sympathy and concern for Pakistan. After eight years of occupation
(in Afghanistan), the Soviet withdrawal is bound to leave a
tremendous vacuum.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
