<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Rappaport-Payment     02-20 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rappaport-Payment,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Lawyer Denies Benefit From Payment To Advisers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A published report today says two men closely
linked with Attorney General Edwin Meese III received $150,000 from
a Swiss businessman pushing an Iraqi oil pipeline, but Meese's
lawyer says the attorney general didn't benefit in any way.
   The Washington Post reported that Bruce Rappaport of Geneva sent
the money in mid-1985 to Franklyn Chinn, Meese's former investment
adviser, and E. Bob Wallach, a close friend of Meese for more than
30 years.
   Sources familiar with the payment said Wallach said the money
represents his legal fee for his work on the pipeline proposal, the
newspaper said. That work included getting Meese's help in setting
up a meeting for Rappaport in June 1985 with then-national security
adviser Robert C. McFarlane, the Post said.
   The Post quoted one source as saying the money was ``sent to
Chinn for the benefit of Wallach.''
   Meese's attorney, James Rocap, said Friday he was aware of the
payment but that ``it has absolutely nothing to do with Mr. Meese.''
   ``None of it (the money) ever went to Mr. Meese,'' he said.
``None of it was ever used for the benefit of Mr. Meese.''
   The Post said the payment is not included on Wallach's 1985
income tax return and was not reported by him until May 1987, when
independent counsel James C. McKay expanded his investigation of
the scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp. to include Meese's dealings with
Wallach and Chinn.
   Wallach and Chinn and a third man were accused in a federal
indictment in New York in December of taking illegal payments from
Wedtech to influence Meese. McKay has been conducting a separate
investigation of Meese's dealings with the two men.
   Rappaport hired Wallach in 1985 to try to drum up U.S. support
for the proposed 540-mile pipeline through Jordan that would run
close to Israeli territory. The pipeline never was built.
   The San Francisco-based Bechtel Group, which was seeking to
build the project, had enlisted the Swiss businessman's help
because of his close ties to Israeli political figures. There had
been concern that Israel might attack the pipeline.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
