<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     02-20 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simon Says He's In Race To `Finish Line'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIOUX FALLS, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Simon, who earlier had threatened
to drop out of the Democratic presidential race unless he started
getting more votes, now says he's in the running ``until the finish
line.''
   The Illinois senator said Friday that he'd gotten so much
support since he said he might drop out that it ``has convinced me
that a great many Americans want a clear-cut choice next November.''
   ``This is a marathon race for the heart and soul of the
Democratic Party, and I'm in it until the finish line in Atlanta,''
Simon told the Minnehaha County Democratic Forum. The national
convention will be held July 18-21 in the Georgia capital.
   After placing third among Democrats in this week's New Hampshire
primary, Simon had said he would drop out of the race if he did not
win South Dakota's primary or Minnesota's caucuses Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jesse Jackson Seek Support From Lesbians, Gays</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A campaign leader for Jesse Jackson says a
precinct caucus victory Tuesday in Minnesota, where about 96
percent of the population is white, would debunk the idea that
Jackson can't be elected president because he is black.
   The Rev. Thomas Van Leer made the statement Friday at
Minneapolis North High School, where Jackson talked to students
about drug abuse. Jackson made several campaign appearances in the
Twin Cities Friday, including a stop at an inner-city Minneapolis
church packed with lesbians and gays.
   ``I stood with you,'' the Democratic candidate said. ``Now make
me a president.''
   The Rev. Arlene Ackerman, pastor of All God's Children
Metropolitan Community Church, said Jackson was the only
presidential candidate to stand with gays and lesbians when they
marched in Washington, D.C., in October.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fahrenkoph Discounts Results Of Nevada Straw Poll</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Republican Party Chairman
Frank Fahrenkopf says Nevada Republicans are ``a long way'' from
determining their delegates to the GOP convention despite a straw
poll in which Pat Robertson's backers claimed victory.
   Vice President George Bush led Nevada's GOP presidential straw
poll with 27 percent of the vote, but Robertson forces claimed
their candidate had won if undecided votes cast by Robertson
supporters were figured in.
   Robertson's 15 percent of the vote Thursday night placed him
behind Bush and Senate GOP Leader Bob Dole, who had 22 percent, and
ahead of Rep. Jack Kemp who got 13 percent. But the Robertson
campaign urged followers to cast undecided votes, so the total of
his support could have been higher than Bush's.
   Fahrenkopf, a Nevada native, said Friday the straw poll was
non-binding and ``we are a long way from determining who the
delegates are just at the state level. What happened in a straw
poll at the Nevada caucuses really doesn't mean a lot.''
</TEXT>
