<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka     02-20 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Sets Himself Ablaze To Mourn Assassinated Actor and Film Star</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 30-year-old Sinhalese man set
himself ablaze to mourn the assassination of a popular movie actor
and politician. Doctors said the man was in critical condition
today.
   Amarasinghe Jayasinghe doused himself with kerosene and set
himself ablaze about midnight Thursday where queues of people had
formed to file past the coffin bearing the body of Vijaya
Kumaranatunga.
   ``The poor quality of the kerosene and quick action by onlookers
kept him alive so far'' said a doctor in the burn unit of Colombo's
general hospital.
   Relatives said Jayasinghe was an ardent fan of Kumaranatunga,
who was killed at his suburban Colombo home Tuesday by two gunmen
police say they suspect belong to the extremist Sinhalese People's
Liberation Front.
   The front has vowed to kill anyone who, like Kumaranatunga,
supports an Indian-brokered peace accord that aims to end Tamil
rebels' four-year-old struggle for an indepedent homeland.
   The July accord would grant the Tamils some degree of autonomy
in northern and eastern provinces where they are most numerous.
   Kumaranatunga, who was 43, headed the opposition Sri Lanka
People's Party. He is to be cremated Sunday afternoon and police
said they expect huge crowds.
   People from all over the country are expected to attend the
cremation. Kumaranatunga starred in more than 100 films, and
theater owners say they will close their establishments Sunday out
of respect.
   Police say the People's Liberation Front has killed about 150
people who support the peace accord, including lawmakers, police
officers and Harsha Abeywardene, chairman of the governing United
National Party.
   The accord has also been rejected by the largest Tamil militia,
the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, who have refused to surrender
their weapons, as called for by its provisions.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindu, claim they are discriminated
against by the Sinhalese Buddhists, who make up 75 percent of the
island's 16 million people. Tamils comprise about 18 percent of the
population.
   India has sent nearly 50,000 troops to the neighboring island to
disarm the rebels, but fighting continues in the east.
</TEXT>
