<DOCNO> AP880220-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-20-88 0521EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Waldheim     02-20 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Waldheim,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Sends Files on Waldheim for New Investigation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Waldheim, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States sent records to help Britain
investigate alleged links between Kurt Waldheim and six British
commandos who were executed in Nazi-occupied Greece, Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher said.
   She also said Britain had no suspicions about Waldheim's record
as an intelligence officer in the German army when he was elected
U.N. secretary-general in 1972.
   The prime minister made the comments Friday in written replies
to questions in the House of Commons.
   Allegations have been made that Waldheim, who held the U.N. job
10 years and now is president of Austria, committed war crimes
during his service in the Balkans. An international panel of
historians appointed by the Austrian government said it found no
proof, but left the question of guilt open.
   Waldheim, 69, has denied wrongdoing since the accusations began
during his presidential campaign two years ago, and has refused to
resign since the historians' report was made public last week.
   The arrival of the microfilmed German army war records from U.S.
military archives was the latest step in an attempt ordered by Mrs.
Thatcher to determine whether Waldheim interrogated the six
commandos.
   The men, a raiding party captured off the Greek island of
Alimina in April 1944, were handed over for interrogation to the
unit in which Waldheim served.
   They refused to talk and were executed by the Germans, a war
crime under the Geneva Convention on prisoners of war.
   ``I am informed that at the time of Dr. Waldheim's election as
U.N. secretary-general no doubts were raised about his wartime
record,'' said Mrs. Thatcher.
   She was answering questions from lawmaker Robert Rhodes James,
who served on Waldheim's personal staff at the United Nations and
now is trying to prove him guilty of war crimes. The historians'
report said Waldheim was in ``close proximity'' to atrocities, must
have known of them and did nothing to stop them.
   British officials said the material sent from the United States
was a copy of the so-called Alimina file dealing with the capture
of the commandos.
   The original file was in a mass of German military documents
American forces captured at the end of the war in 1945. The
documents were kept in the United States until sent to West German
archives at Freiburg in the late 1960s.
   Historian Gerald Fleming says records of the vital second
interrogation of the commandos, including who conducted it, were
missing from the original file in Freiburg.
   Fleming was the British member of the international commission,
which reported finding the initial ``W'' in Waldheim's hand on an
earlier record of interviews with the six men, indicating he at
least had read it.
   The historians' report said Waldheim was well aware of Hitler's
orders to execute commandos.
   A note in English attached to the Alimina file said: ``Do not
film this sheet. Interrogations reports removed because of security
classification.'' It was not immediately clear whether the U.S.
microfilmed material was more complete than the original file.
   An inquiry in 1986, based on incomplete British files, did not
establish a link between Waldheim and the commandos.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
