<1ST_LINE>r i PM_Thailand-LaosBorder     02-20 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM_Thailand-Laos Border,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thai-Laotian Officers Inspect Disputed Border Area From
Helicopters.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thai and Laotian officers today flew
over a disputed border area to arrange for the disengagement of
troops that had been locked in a bloody, 3{-month battle, a Thai
officer said.
   Since a truce began Friday, no fighting was reported in the area
where hundreds of soldiers on both sides had died since fighting
commenced in November around contested hills at the frontier.
   Members of the Laotian joint committee flew over the area in a
Soviet-made MI-8 helicopter while the Thais inspected it from a
U.S.-manufactured Huey said Thai army spokesman Col. Rithee
Rungkaputi.
   After the cease-fire began, two parallel rows of Thai and
Laotian flags were staked to mark a zone which troops are forbidden
to cross, said Thai Gen. Charuay Wongsayant.
   The fighting had been the bloodiest since communist forces
triumphed in Laos in 1975.
   Gen. Chaovalit Yongchaiyuth, the Thai army commander, said he
would fly to the Laotian capital of Vientiane Tuesday at the
invitation of Gen. Sisavat Keobounphan, the chief of the Laotian
army general staff.
   Sisavat was Chaovalit's counterpart at talks early last week in
Bangkok that produced the cease fire.
   Thai and Laotian military delegations agreed that their troops
should be separated by 2 miles within 48 hours of the start of the
truce.
   The affected area is between Thailand's northern province of
Phitsanulok and Laos' Sayaboury province, an area about 240 miles
north of Bangkok.
</TEXT>
