<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Sikhs 1stLd-Writethru a0430 02-20 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Sikhs, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0430,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikh Militants Kill 25 In Two Days of Punjab Attacks</HEAD>
<HEAD>PRECEDE New Delhi</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with higher death toll, details. CORRECTS
name of slain farmer. ADDS byline.
^By DEEPAK SHARMA</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh gunmen killed two people at a bus
stop outside Amritsar today, raising to 25 the number of people
slain in two days of bombings and shootings in Punjab state, police
and news reports said.
   The victims included 10 people shot to death then set ablaze in
a farmhouse and 10 others who died in apparently well-planned bomb
attacks in four cities in the northern state. More than 60 people
were wounded in the bombings.
   An unexploded bomb was found today in a fifth city, Batala, the
United News of India reported. It said the four-pound tin of
explosives was left in a store by a woman customer in the city 25
miles northeast of Amritsar.
   The news agency also said two men were shot to death this
afternoon at a bus stop on the edge of the Sikh holy city.
   The latest killings brought to nearly 250 the number of people
killed this year in Punjab in attacks blamed on Sikh militants, who
demand a separate nation for their minority religion.
   In the village of Sahsra, nine members of a farm family were
killed with automatic rifles and revolvers Friday night, along with
a man staying at the house, police said.
   Residents in the village 20 miles southeast of Amritsar said
about six Sikh gunmen stormed into the home of farmer Kewal Singh
while the family slept. The assailants set the bodies, the farmouse
and its furnishings ablaze, the villagers said.
   The victims included the farmer, his wife, two daughters, four
sons, a niece and a guest identified as Sukhdev Singh. Police said
earlier reports that 11 died apparently resulted from confusion.
   While Sikh militants frequently claim their Sikh victims are
police informers, neighbors insisted Kewal Singh was only a simple
villager.
   Gurcharan Singh, the village leader, said he was ``a poor farmer
and tongawalla,'' or wagon driver.
   UNI reported two other people were shot to death by Sikh
militants Friday at Bhuri Kalan near Amritsar and a man was killed
near Patiala, about 140 miles southeast of Amritsar.
   Friday's bomb attacks were in the cities of Amritsar, Patiala,
Gurdaspur and Hoshiarpur and prompted police in New Delhi to issue
a ``red alert'' that the attacks might spread to the capital.
   Sikh extremists have been fighting for a separate state in
Punjab since 1982. Sikhs are a majority in Punjab but comprise only
2 percent of the nationwide population of 780 million, more than 80
percent of whom are Hindu.
   The Sikh faith has elements of both Hinduism and Islam and was
founded about 500 years ago as a peaceful alternative to the two
warring religions.
   But the Sikhs' 10th and final prophet, Guru Gobind Singh,
declared Sikhism a warrior faith in which male adherents should all
carry knives and bear the name Singh, ``lion'' in Punjabi.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
