<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Kidnap 1stLd-Writethru a0470 02-20 0872</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Kidnap, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0470,0897</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Militia Leader Says Snags Slowed Abduction, Allowed Troops to Seal
Area</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with details of snafus after
kidnapping; UNIFIL spokesman's comments. No Pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A militia commander today said his forces
arrested several accomplices in the kidnapping of a U.S. Marine
officer who heads a United Nations observer team, but that the
mastermind had escaped.
   Daoud Daoud, the top military commander of the mainstream Shiite
Amal militia in south Lebanon, also that the kidnapping was
well-planned in advance but that a series of snags slowed down the
abductors' flight, giving Amal time to seal the area.
   He said he believes Lt. Col. William R. Higgins still is in
south Lebanon, although he was kidnapped Wednesday.
   ``We have arrested several accomplices, but the leader of the
kidnap operation has left the south,'' Daoud told The Associated
Press in an interview at his home in Bedias, seven miles northeast
of Tyre.
   ``We know them all by name now, and we believe (Lt.) Col.
Higgins is still in south Lebanon,'' he said.
   Amal militiamen and U.N. peacekeeping troops have sealed off a
300-square-mile area around Tyre, searching through cave-strewn
valleys and olive and citrus groves.
   Higgins, 43, heads a 76-man unarmed U.N. observer team that
monitors border violations of a 1949 armistice agreement between
Lebanon and Israel.
   The group is attached to the 5,800-member U.N. Interim Force in
Lebanon, or UNIFIL, deployed in 1978 after an Israeli incursion
into south Lebanon.
   The pro-Iranian Organization of the Oppressed on Earth on Friday
claimed responsibility for Higgins' abduction, accusing him of
being a CIA spy. American and U.N. officials denied the charge.
   The Pentagon said Higgins, of Danville, Ky., had been a junior
military aide to former U.S. Secretary of Defense Caspar Weinberger
but that his abduction did not pose a major security risk to the
United States.
   The first claim of responsibility for the kidnapping came
Thursday in a call from an anonymous man claiming to speak for a
previously unknown group, the Islamic Revolutionary Brigades.
   ``We believe Higgins is still in south Lebanon because the
accomplice who was assigned to transport him to Beirut after the
abduction is detained by us,'' Daoud said, refusing to identify any
of the suspects or their affiliations.
   Security sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said many
of the 40 men detained have links to the Iranian-backed Hezbollah,
or Party of God, an umbrella organization for Shiite extremists.
   Hezbollah's Voice of Islam radio station, based in Baalbek, in
east Lebanon, claimed today that 150 Hezbollah members were rounded
up in house raids in the Tyre region.
   ``Amal's men have stormed Hezbollah's operations center in the
south, seized documents, equipment and cameras. They also raided
the house of Hezbollah's south Lebanon leader Abbas Musawi,'' the
radio said. It made no mention of Higgins.
   Daoud said Higgins' abduction was ``carefully thought out,
planned and staged.''
   He said among the detainees were those assigned to monitor
Higgins' movements, and ``they have confessed that they knew four
days in advance that he was coming to Tyre on Wednesday.''
   Higgins was driving from Tyre to UNIFIL headquarters in the
border town of Naqoura when gunmen in a brown Volvo car blocked the
highway and seized him.
   ``The kidnappers ran into a chain of snags after the abduction.
Their first car, the brown Volvo, got stuck in the mud. They made a
bulldozer driver push them out, but the exhaust was broken and they
had to move Higgins to a white Peugeot,'' Daoud said.
   ``This (second) car collided with a truck loaded with oranges
southeast of Tyre. The kidnappers then moved Higgins to a red
Mercedes and fled to their unknown hideout,'' Daoud added.
   ``These snags cost the kidnappers about 1{ hours, during which
we managed to seal off all exits from Tyre region south of the
Litani River,'' Daoud said.
   He said the mastermind had sent four other brown Volvo cars
speeding through several neighboring villages.
   ``He wanted to shake off any pursuers. However, the accidents
gave us the needed time to seal off the area,'' Daoud said.
   ``I am 60 percent certain that Higgins is still south of the
Litani. It is very difficult for them to smuggle him out on foot
through the valleys. Nevertheless, we're keeping this in mind,'' he
added.
   UNIFIL spokesman Timur Goksel today said: ``We are maintaining
road checks and heavy emphasis on collection of information. We
believe he is probably still south of the Litani,'' Goksel said.
   In Washington, President Reagan said Thursday that the United
States will not withdraw Americans from the U.N. observer group,
despite the abduction. Fifteen other nations contribute to the unit.
   In its type-written Arabic statement, the Organization of the
Oppressed on Earth said Higgins is ``one of the biggest spies
planting daily terror in our land.''
   The statement was delivered to a Western news agency in Beirut,
accompanied by photocopies of two identity cards of Higgins.
   The group, believed made up of Shiite zealots, previously has
claimed responsibility for hijackings, bombings and the abduction
of 12 Lebanese Jews. It has claimed to have killed eight of the
Jews kidnapped in 1984.
</TEXT>
