<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Arms     02-20 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Arms,0660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Red Army General Says Arms Treaty Will Save Lots of Rubles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviets' top arms control official said his
country is counting on Secretary of State George P. Shultz to
arrive ready to explore new initiatives in U.S.-Soviet disarmament
talks.
   Viktor Karpov, a former arms negotiator who now heads the Soviet
Foreign Ministry's arms control department, said late Friday that
Shultz's visit, which begins Sunday, ``must set the pace for
further Soviet-U.S. dialogue.''
   During the U.S. official's three-day visit, he is scheduled to
talk with Mikhail S. Gorbachev and other top Soviet officials about
a proposed agreement to cut the superpowers' long-range nuclear
missiles by 50 percent.
   The talks follow the Dec. 8 signing of a treaty to ban
superpower medium- and shorter-range nuclear missiles by Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and President Reagan in Washington.
   In a special panel of the Supreme Soviet parliament earlier
Friday, two Red Army officials said that ratification of the Dec. 8
treaty could save the Soviet Union more than $80 million and would
free ``tens of thousands'' of soldiers from their present duties.
   Marshal Sergei F. Akhromeyev, the military chief of staff, and
Maj. Gen. Vladimir I. Medvedev were among top officials who spoke
before the panel, which is considering ratification of the pact.
   Those who spoke at the hearing at the Kremlin endorsed the
treaty, but Akhromeyev said the Soviet military is worried about
NATO moves to compensate for the weapons slated for destruction by
the pact.
   ``The idea of compensation is wild,'' said the first deputy
foreign minister, Yuli M. Vorontsov. ``A doctor who operates on a
person to cure him of an ulcer does not then say, `What can I put
in to compensate for the ulcer?'''
   On Feb. 9, the foreign relations commissions of the two houses
of the Soviet legislature created a special 10-member subcommittee
to seek the opinion of experts and ordinary Soviet citizens about
the treaty.
   The treaty must be ratified by the Supreme Soviet's Presidium to
become law. But because it already has been approved by the ruling
Communist Party Politburo, passage is assured.
   Friday's two-hour hearing seemed designed to assuage the fears
of some Soviets that their leaders made too many concessions in the
treaty. A small group of foreign reporters was allowed to attend.
   ``Those against are few,'' said chairman Georgy M. Korniyenko,
summing up Soviet public opinion. ``Those who are against just
don't trust the imperialists ... but then there are not a few who
have concerns.''
   Under the pact, the Soviet Union must destroy 1,752 missiles,
compared with 859 for the United States.
   But Akhromeyev said that under the agreement, the Soviets will
eliminate 650 modern medium-range missiles, while the Americans
will destroy 689 new weapons, he said.
   U.S. Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci and other NATO officials
have said the West needs to modernize its battlefield nuclear
weapons or improve its conventional arms to make up for the banned
missiles.
   Akhromeyev said there was ``not a word'' in the INF treaty that
would bar such measures.
   Akromeyev said 3 percent to 4 percent of the ``tens of
thousands'' of military men to be released from their duty with the
missiles would be put on pension, but that younger men could
continue with their military careers.
   Medvedev told the panel that missiles and other Soviet military
equipment worth $33 million to $41.5 million would be destroyed
because of the treaty.
   He said the Soviet Union would save $83 million, and that
military equipment used for the missiles that does not have to be
destroyed is worth $250 million.
   The subcommittee adjourned without a date set for its next
session. The panel will report back to the Supreme Soviet's foreign
relations commissions, which must recommend whether the treaty
should be ratified.
</TEXT>
