<2ND_LINE>PM-Namibia-Bombing, 1st Ld - Writethru,0664</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede PRETORIA</HEAD>
<HEAD>South African Air Force Attacks SWAPO Base</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: COMBINES urgent series; ADDS background on bombing. No
pickup. ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The air force carried out a
revenge attack on two SWAPO guerrilla bases in Angola this morning,
retaliating for a bank bombing that killed 18 people in Namibia,
the defense force chief said.
   Gen. Jannie Geldenhuys said air force fighter aircraft
successfully carried out attacks on South-West African People's
Organization targets in Lubango and Ongiva in southern Angola.
   He said the attacks were in retaliation Friday's bombing of the
First National Bank in Oshakati, South-West Africa, where 18 people
were killed and 31 injured.
   Geldenhuys said SWAPO, which has been fighting for 22 years
against South African occupation of the territory, also known as
Namibia, was responsible for the lunch-hour bomb.
   A statement Friday from the SWAPO office in Luanda, Angola,
denied involvement in the bombing, and said it was part of a South
African propaganda campaign to ``smear the name of SWAPO.''
   The guerrillas fight in South-West Africa, also known as
Namibia, from bases in southern Angola that periodically are raided
by the South African Defense Force.
   Eight Mirage fighters took part in the attack on two targets
near Lubango, 186 miles north of the Namibian-Angolan border; and
five Impala aircraft attacked targets at Ongiva, 26 miles north of
the border, the statement said.
   Geldenhuys said the Lubango targets were ``SWAPO's most
important training center in Angola, the Tobias Hainyeko Training
Center, and a terrorist holding area about 10 kms (6.2 miles) west
of there.''
   He said SWAPO guerrillas receive training in the handling of
explosives at the Tobias Hainyeko Center, which he said, ``can be
regarded as the breeding ground for terrorism against the
inhabitants of South-West Africa-Namibia.''
   SWAPO had launched a number of raids from Ongiva recently on
civilians in South-West Africa, the general said.
   ``By these attacks the security forces demonstrated their
willingness never to allow SWAPO terrorism to go unpunished,''
Geldenhuys said. ``Terrorists will be tracked down and destroyed.''
   Friday's bank blast was the deadliest in 22 years of war between
the black guerrillas and the minority white government of South
Africa.
   Among the dead in the blast in the far-northern town of Oshakati
were 10 women, three men and a child. All the victims were black,
except for one white woman who was identified today in a
pro-government newspaper as the wife of a member of a special
police unit.
   Four of the bodies were discovered in the rubble Friday night,
said The Citizen newspaper.
   Of the 31 people injured, 20 of them were black, said an army
spokesman, Cmdt. Lieb Bester.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility for the blast,
which destroyed the bank building. Five people were injured when an
explosion occurred in the street near the same bank a year ago.
   Chris Ball, managing director of the First National Bank, flew
to Windhoek to visit the scene Friday afternoon. He called the
bombing ``a barbarous and senseless attack on the community of
Oshakati, achieving nothing.''
   All those killed were civilians, Bester said. Most were believed
to be local government employees who had just been paid.
   A police inspector, Keirie Du Rand, said about 55 pounds of
plastic explosive was used in the blast, which occurred shortly
before 1 p.m. He said a fire raged for several hours after the
explosion, hampering police access to the scene.
   Oshakati is in north-central Namibia, about 25 miles south of
the Angolan border. It is home to the largest military base in the
region, a staging point for South Africa's current military
intervention in Angola's civil war.
   SWAPO has claimed responsibility for numerous previous bombings
in the territory, including a blast last month at a store at a
military base in Windhoek.
</TEXT>
