<DOCNO> AP880220-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-20-88 0632EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Earthquake     02-20 0133</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Earthquake,0137</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Earthquake Jolts Soviet Central Asian Area</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderately strong earthquake today shook the
mountains of the Soviet Central Asian republic of Tadzhikistan, but
no injuries or damage were reported, the official Soviet news
agency Tass said.
   The tremor occurred at 4:50 a.m. Moscow time (8:50 p.m. EST
Friday) and was centered 99 miles east of the republic's capital,
Dushanbe, Tass said.
   It said the Dushanbe seismic station measured the magnitude of
the earthquake at 5 on the Soviet scale. The Soviet scale measures
observable effects of an earthquake.
   Tadzhikistan, with an area of 55,240 square miles, is known for
farming and cattle ranching. Rich deposits of coal, lead and zinc
also are found in the republic, whose 1981 population was 3.4
million.
   It borders Afghanistan and China.
</TEXT>
