<2ND_LINE>PM-Amtrak Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0481,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Dead In Train Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughut with fire reported in two cars and to ADD
that shelter set up. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HASTINGS, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One person was killed and 14 people were
taken to a hospital after a fire broke out today in two cars of an
Amtrak train near here, authorities said.
   The fire aboard the California Zephyr was reported around 3 a.m.
and was under control by 4:30 a.m., said Fire Chief Jim Mitera.
   It was unclear whether the fatality was a crew member or a
passenger, Mitera said. He said the injured apparently suffered
either smoke inhalation or burns.
   Passengers aboard the train saw thick smoke coming from the
train, according to passenger Vicki Miller of Omaha. The smoke
appeared to be coming from crew cars just in front of the passenger
sleeping cars, she said.
   Police reported two cars were burning, said Bryce Wellnitz, a
dispatcher with the Nebraska State Patrol in Lincoln.
   Amtrak crew members disconnected the two cars and the Zephyr,
which travels from Chicago to Oakland, Calif., continued on its
route.
   Investigators did not know where the fire started or what may
have caused it, Mitera said.
   The Red Cross set up a shelter in the Hastings city auditorium,
Wellnitz said. Hastings, a town of about 18,000, is in southeast
Nebraska.
   A call to Amtrak's office in Omaha reached an official who
refused to give his name or comment on the fire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
