<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Violence 1stLd-Writethru a0411 02-20 0755</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Violence, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0411,0779</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demonstrator Reported Killed In West Bank March</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with report of death in
Ramallah, EDITS to trim. PICKS up 11th graf pvs bgng, _Israeli
soldiers...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto covering.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers shot and killed a Palestinian
demonstrator today in the West Bank town of Ramallah during a march
on the municipal building, the Arab-run Palestine Press Service and
hospital sources said.
   A spokesman for the Israeli army could not immediately confirm
the death.
   The Palestinian news agency identified the victim as Abdullah
Atta Abdullah, 20, and said he was shot in the head.
   It said Abdullah was one of several hundred demonstrators
demanding the resignation of the municipal council of Ramallah,
which is 10 miles north of Jerusalem.
   Sources at a hospital at Ramallah, who spoke on condition they
not be identified, said Abdullah was shot in the forehead.
   The army command said Israeli troops clashed with 200 Moslem
worshipers at the Tomb of the Patriarchs in Hebron in the occupied
West Bank.
   Moslems and Jews both believe the site is the burial place of
the biblical patriarchs Abraham, Isaac and Jacob and three of their
four wives.
   Arabs spread prayer rugs on the floor and began to pray Friday
during Jewish services in a chamber normally used at different
hours as a place of worship by Jews and Arabs.
   The site attracts Jewish and Moslem religious fundamentalists
and has been a constant source of friction since Israel captured
the West Bank and Gaza Strip in the 1967 Middle East war.
   An army spokeswoman said soldiers ordered the Moslem worshipers
out of the hall and used force, but not gunfire or tear gas, to
evict them when they refused.
   The Arabs attacked the soldiers, the spokeswoman said on
condition of anonymity in keeping with army regulations.
   By U.N. count and not including today's reported death, 55 Arabs
have been killed by Israelis since protests began in the occupied
territories Dec. 8.
   In other developments on Friday:
   _Israeli soldiers tangled with Palestinian protesters in Nablus
and in the Gaza Strip, but no casualties were reported.
   _Military sources denied charges by Neil Kinnock, head of
Britain's Labor Party, that Israeli troops were using dumdum
bullets against Arab protesters. Dumdum bullets expand explosively
when they hit a target, causing greater damage.
   _Fayez Abu Rahmeh, one of six Palestinians reportedly favored to
meet U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz in Israel next week,
said he would cancel the meeting if ordered to do so by the
Palestinian Liberation Organization.
   In Nablus, 40 miles north of Jerusalem, hundreds of protesters
waved Palestinian flags, brandished photographs of PLO chief Yasser
Arafat, and chanted slogans.
   They moved toward Israeli troops at the exits of the old city,
throwing stones, bricks and bottles. Soldiers retaliated with tear
gas and chased youths through the streets.
   At Jabaliya refugee camp in the Gaza Strip, hundreds of people
demonstrated after prayers, carrying Palestinian flags and throwing
rocks.
   The army command denied Palestinian reports that soldiers used
tear gas and clubs to disperse the protesters at Jabaliya.
   In Gaza City, protesters threw stones and burned tires. Shati
refugee camp remained under curfew imposed by the army last week.
   Kinnock, in Israel on a visit, made the charge about dumdum
bullets at a news conference Friday. He said he saw X-rays of a
wound which ``showed shattering of the bone and flesh consistent
with the use of an explosive bullet.'' At another point he said the
injury was consistent with ``the wound inflicted by a dumdum
bullet.''
   The comment by Abu Rahmeh, a Palestinian leader from the Gaza
Strip, to The Associated Press came after the outlawed PLO issued a
statement Friday.
   The statement said the visit, and a new peace initiative
promoted by Shultz, were aimed ``at liquidating the Palestinian
cause and the heroic uprising'' in the occupied lands. It said no
Palestinian leaders in the occupied territories would meet Shultz
on his visit.
   Abu Rahmeh said: ``I must obey the (PLO) request, whatever it
is.''
   Earlier, he said he would urge Shultz ``to agree to the
convening of an international peace conference and help the parties
reach a settlement between themselves.''
   The PLO backs an international peace conference if it includes
an independent PLO delegation.
   Israel's two main parties, the right-wing Likud and centrist
Labor Party are split over the convening of a peace conference but
united in their refusal to negotiate with the PLO.
</TEXT>
