<FILEID>AP-NR-02-20-88 1237EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Rappaport-Payment     02-20 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rappaport-Payment,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyer Denies Meese Benefited From Payment To Associates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer for Attorney General Edwin Meese III
said Saturday that Meese received no money or benefit from a
reported $150,000 payment to two close Meese associates in
connection with promotion of an Iraqi pipeline project.
   The attorney, James Rocap, said he was aware of the payment but
that ``it has absolutely nothing to do with Mr. Meese.''
   Swiss businessman Bruce Rappaport sent the money in mid-1985 to
Franklyn Chinn, Meese's former investment adviser, and E. Bob
Wallach, a close friend of Meese for more than 30 years, according
to sources familiar with independent prosecutor James McKay's
investigation of Meese.
   Rappaport was enlisted by the San Francisco-based Bechtel Group,
which was seeking to build the project.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, quoted Wallach
as saying the money from Rappaport represented his legal fee for
his work on the pipeline proposal, including getting Meese's help
to set up a meeting for Rappaport in June 1985 with then-national
security adviser Robert C. McFarlane.
   Rocap characterized as ``not a big deal'' the fact that Wallach
had been paid a fee through Rappaport and that the $150,000 had
been deposited in a trust account with Chinn.
   ``Ed Meese never got any money from the pipeline project or from
Bruce Rappaport. He never got any money from Bob Wallach with the
exception of a few lunches,'' said Rocap.
   The lawyer said that the only money Meese got through his
partnership with Chinn was the previously disclosed stock profits
that Chinn earned for the attorney general through various stock
trades.
   The Washington Post reported Saturday that the payment was not
included on Wallach's 1985 income tax return and was not reported
by him until May 1987, when McKay expanded his investigation of the
scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp. to include Meese's dealings with
Wallach and Chinn.
   A federal indictment in New York accused Wallach and Chinn and a
third man of taking illegal payments from Wedtech to influence
Meese.
   Rappaport hired Wallach in 1985 to try to drum up U.S. support
for the proposed 540-mile pipeline through Jordan that would run
close to Israeli territory. The pipeline never was built.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
