<FILEID>AP-NR-02-20-88 1240EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-ReaganRadio     02-20 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan Radio,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Urges Congress To Forget Election-Year Spending Pressure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan today asked Congress to ward
off election year pressure for increased spending and enact the
$1.1 trillion budget presented earlier in the week.
   ``If Congress upholds its commitments and stands firm against
pressures for increased spending _ pressures that reach a peak
during election years _ solid results will be forthcoming,'' Reagan
said in his weekly radio speech.
   ``If our proposed budget is enacted, deficit spending will have
dropped from $221 billion in fiscal year 1986 to $130 billion in
fiscal year 1989,'' the president said.
   He said consultations between Congress and the White House
before the budget submission _ which both branches have hailed as a
method of avoiding budget fights as in previous years _
demonstrates ``responsible leadership expected by the electorate.''
   Reagan said the budget will ``keep the lid'' on spending, while
recognizing that some increases are needed to avoid jeopardizing
national security.
   He repeated his criticism of last year's budget process, saying
late amendments to the spending bill required him to sign a package
without the review it should have been granted, or face shutdown of
the federal government.
   With the new budget, he said, ``we have an opportunity to put
our fiscal house in order.''
   Reagan also repeated his assertion that his administration has
presided over the biggest economic expansion since World War II and
once again hailed his administration's record on employment.
</TEXT>
