<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Paley,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paley Remains in Critical Condition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Paley, the 86-year-old founder and
chairman of CBS Inc., remained in critical condition Saturday after
undergoing emergency gall bladder surgery more than a week ago.
   A spokeswoman for New York Hospital-Cornell Medical Center said
that Paley was in critical but stable condition.
   On Friday, another spokeswoman, Diana Goldin, said Paley was
``off the respirator and recuperating well from emergency abdominal
surgery performed 10 days ago, but is being treated for
pre-existing pulmonary and renal conditions aggravated by this
recent illness.''
   The hospital said that Paley was receiving kidney dialysis.
   He had been in critical condition since undergoing surgery on
Feb. 11.
   Paley bought a fledling radio station in 1928 and built it into
the Columbia Broadcasting System. In 1983, he stepped down as
chairman, but made a comeback in 1986 with Loew's Corp.'s chairman
Lawrence Tisch after he became disenchanted with company policies.
</TEXT>
