<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Poland 2ndLd-Writethru a0499 02-20 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0499,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top Opposition Activists Reported Detained Around Country</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with spokesman saying seven,
sted eight detained; Picks up 7th graf pvs, `Solidarity regional
...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police across the country detained at
least seven top opposition activists in an apparent effort to
prevent a weekend Solidarity meeting from convening, opposition
spokesmen said today.
   Among those reported held were two prominent figures in the
outlawed trade union federation who were removed by officers from a
car also carrying Solidarity Chairman Lech Walesa.
   Walesa, interviewed by telephone from his home in Gdansk, said
union spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz and Gdansk regional Solidarity
leader Bogdan Lis were taken from his car shortly after noon, but
he was left alone.
   ``We have reforms by (means of) arresting,'' Walesa said
sarcastically. ``This is something well known to communist
authorities.''
   Also reported held was Zbigniew Bujak, Warsaw-region Solidarity
leader who was the union's underground chief after the imposition
of martial law in December 1981.
   He was detained at the Warsaw train station before he could
board a train to Gdansk to attend a meeting of the Solidarity
National Executive Commission, said the Rev. Henryk Jankowski, an
adviser to Walesa.
   Jankowski initially reported that Solidarity adviser Jacek Kuron
was detained at the same time. But Warsaw opposition spokesmen said
later that Jankowski was mistaken and Kuron had not been held.
   Solidarity regional leaders from Krakow, Lublin, Bydgoszcz and
Wroclaw also were reported detained.
   Commission meetings are not announced in advance, and neither
Walesa nor Jankowski would not state the reason for the meeting in
the Baltic port.
   However Solidarity, which has remained active despite its being
banned in 1982, is known to be evaluating its strategy in the face
of steep price increases imposed Feb. 1.
   The increases have caused widespread discontent, but no major
unrest. Past price increases have triggered violence as well as the
strikes that spawned Solidarity in August 1980.
   Jankowski, who spoke by telephone from Gdansk, said 19 people
were detained nationwide, but there were contradictory reports from
other opposition sources.
   A spokesman in the government press office, Zbigniew
Augustynowicz, said he had no immediate comment on the reports but
would look into them.
   Authorities in Poland often use brief detentions to block
illegal meetings. Since a 1986 amnesty, no one has been held more
than 48 hours solely on political charges.
   Wladyslaw Frasyniuk, a regional leader of Solidarity in the
southwestern city of Wroclaw, was detained Friday evening by a
group of uniformed and plainclothes police, said his wife, Krystyna.
   Police later telephoned their home and said without explanation
that Frasyniuk was being held for 48 hours, she said.
   It was not known if Frasyniuk, who is also a member of
Solidarity's executive commission, had planned to attend the
meeting in Gdansk. However, he was to attend a meeting Sunday of a
banned farmers' group, Rural Solidarity, in southeastern Poland.
   Another executive commission member, Stanislaw Weglarz, was
detained Friday in his home city of Lublin, in eastern Poland, said
opposition spokesman Janusz Winiarski.
   Stefan Jurczak, an executive commission member from near Krakow,
also was detained Friday, another opposition source said.
   Briefly detained was Janusz Stepniak, from near Lublin, a leader
of Rural Solidarity, said Winiarski, who said Stepniak was warned
against attending the Rural Solidarity meeting in Rzeszow.
   The Provisional National Council of Rural Solidarity, an
farmers' union modeled on the Soviet bloc's first and only
independent labor federation, has called a national meeting of
farmers to mark the seventh anniversary of the 1981
Rzeszow-Ustrzyki agreements.
   In those accords, the government officially recognized Rural
Solidarity.
   After the imposition of martial law, Rural Solidarity was
banned, although some members have continued their activities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
