<FILEID>AP-NR-02-20-88 1331EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Amtrak-Eyewitness     02-20 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amtrak-Eyewitness,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Ended Group Ski Trip</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Amtrak Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Associated Press Writer Vicki Miller was aboard
the California Zephyr on her way to a skiing weekend in Colorado
when a fire broke out. This is her account of the incident.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By VICKI MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HASTINGS, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most people in the first coach car of an
Amtrak train were trying to sleep in the wee hours of Saturday
morning when the California Zephyr pulled into the small station
here to pick up passengers.
   The quiet was shattered by the sound of sirens, but no one knew
what was going on until they began to smell smoke.
   There were no crew members in sight. One woman in our group,
which was headed for a ski trip in Winter Park, Colo., went to
investigate. She returned to tell us calmly that there was a fire
in a nearby car.
   It didn't sound serious, and jokes were tossed around while
passengers in the car began to stir.
   We remained in the car, wondering if it was safe, reassuring
each other that we would be warned of trouble.
   Minutes later, a woman crew member ran through the coach, her
face blackened with soot. She dashed outside and then returned,
saying she'd barely escaped from the crew car where the fire
apparently began.
   Chattering with cold, she said she had no shoes and that her
feet were cold. Outside it was about 31 degrees.
   The woman left, but returned quickly to ask passengers for
blankets. Her voice was panicky as she told us people outside the
train needed them.
   I glanced out the window and saw smoke billowing from the crew
car two cars ahead. Soon the faint smell of smoke drifted into our
car and we decided it was time to get out.
   As we left the train, it became apparent that the fire was
serious. Some crew members, blankets drapped over their shoulders,
appeared dazed. One man sat bent over on the steps leading to the
upper deck of our coach car. Others were visibly shaken.
   Outside was a maze of fire trucks, hoses and rescue vehicles.
Firefighters on ladders attempted to cut into the crew car's
windows with power tools.
   Emergency personnel and volunteers carried stretchers to
ambulances. An Amtrak employee yelled to firefighters that he
thought there were still people inside the car.
   Soon, more people were helped from the car. Many were dressed in
bedclothes, and some men were bare-chested.
   By the time a spokesman announced that the train would proceed
without the crew car and sleeper car, our group of six had decided
to bail out of our weekend trip. We hitched a ride across town in
the back of an ambulance, with another vehicle toting our gear.
   We turned our hopes from fresh powder to finding a rental car;
after we got the last one in town, my companions headed back home.
   One person was dead, others were hurt. My traveling companions
kept asking, ``Why weren't we told whether we were in danger or
were safe?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880220-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-20-88 1338EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Mofford Bjt   02-20 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mofford, Bjt,0765</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arizona's Acting Governor Says She's Learning the Ropes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Acting Gov. Rose Mofford is getting high
marks in her role as temporary chief executive from many
legislators but not from the man she replaced, impeached Gov. Evan
Mecham.
   Mrs. Mofford, a Democrat and Arizona's longtime secretary of
state, became acting governor Feb. 5 when Mecham, a Republican, was
impeached by the House. She moved into the governor's office and
will remain acting governor until the Senate reaches a verdict.
   ``My lifestyle has changed,'' Mrs. Mofford, 65, told a group of
mayors Friday, saying she's switched her bedtime reading to
subjects like the state budget or Arizona's Medicaid alternative
program.
   When Mecham was impeached he was considered legally ``disabled''
and Mrs. Mofford assumed all of his gubernatorial powers, including
the right to sign bills and hire or fire state employees.
   Mrs. Mofford brought in her own volunteer staff and replaced one
state agency head _ Department of Administration Director Max
Hawkins, who drafted Mecham into the 1986 gubernatorial race and
was widely blamed for many of Mecham's problems. She also accepted
the resignation of Mecham's controversial Washington lobbyist, Fred
Craft.
   That angered Mecham, who has moved his own staff to an office
building in suburban Glendale. In a letter to Mrs. Mofford last
week, he complained that she was ``turning a temporary acting
governorship into a complete disruption and replacement of my
administration.''
   ``May I ask you to recognize that I have only been accused and
not convicted of any act,'' Mecham said, adding that he expects to
be cleared and return to the governorship.
   Mrs. Mofford replied to Mecham, ``I am responsible for acting as
the chief executive of this state ... I did not ask for this job,
but I intend to discharge it to the best of my ability during these
difficult times.''
   Lawmakers say they generally are pleased with the work of Mrs.
Mofford, who many had hoped would act mainly as caretaker.
   ``Mrs. Mofford addresses problems in a calm, deliberate
manner,'' said Rep. Jim Skelly, a conservative Republican who
headed the House select committee on Mecham's impeachment. ``That's
a change. She's not going off half-cocked.''
   ``Haven't you noticed? There's a different air in state
government,'' said Senate Minority Leader Alan Stephens, a
Democrat. ``People aren't looking for the next bomb to drop.''
   Mecham faces a Feb. 29 impeachment trial on allegations that he
concealed a $350,000 campaign loan, misused $80,000 from the
governor's protocol fund by lending it to his auto dealership, and
that he tried to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat
by a state official.
   He is also scheduled for a March 9 criminal trial on six felony
counts in connection with the $350,000 loan.
   If Mecham is convicted in court or by the Senate, Mrs. Mofford
becomes governor in her own right.
   However, that would raise a new series of questions if it
occurred before the May 17 recall election. Attorney General Bob
Corbin has issued a non-binding opinion saying that if Mecham
resigns or is removed before the recall, Mrs. Mofford would be
subject to removal from office in the recall vote.
   Rep. Gary Giordano, a Republican who opposed Mecham's
impeachment, said he realized Mrs. Mofford was entitled to her own
staff, but added, ``I don't think she had a particular mandate to
bring in the Babbitt administration.''
   Many of Mrs. Mofford's volunteer aides had worked for former
Gov. Bruce Babbitt, a Democrat.
   But House Minority Leader Art Hamilton, a Democrat, said he
believes Mrs. Mofford is handling the job wisely.
   ``It's ticklish and it's difficult and it's like no other chief
executive in this state has ever found themselves in,'' Hamilton
said.
   Mrs. Mofford pleased Democrats and angered some Republicans when
she said one of her top priorities would be to seek creation of a
Martin Luther King state holiday. Mecham created a storm of
controversy in January 1986 when he canceled a holiday for state
workers on grounds it was illegally declared by Babbitt through
executive order.
   Otherwise, there has been little controversy over her policies,
including her statement that a tax increase probably would be
needed to balance Arizona's budget.
   ``I don't know all the problems that are facing us,'' Mrs.
Mofford acknowledged Friday. ``I know that there are criticisms out
there, but I don't think that that will be the last time that I
will ever be criticized.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
