<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Basques     02-20 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Basques,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leader of Terrorist Group, Four Others Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAYONNE, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of a French Basque terrorist
group and four members of his organization were arrested Saturday
after a shootout with police, authorities said.
   Philippe Bidart, leader of Iparretarrak, had been sought for
more than six years. The former schoolteacher was convicted twice
in absentia, once for the murder of two police officers, and is
suspected in two other slayings of policemen.
   Iparretarrak, which means ``Those of the North'' in the Basque
language, is fighting for independence for the Basque country in
southwestern France and northern Spain.
   It has been less active than the Spanish Basque terrorist
movement ETA but has claimed responsibility for dozens of attacks.
   About 20 gendarmes _ members of a police force under direction
of the French army _ surrounded Bidart and his companions in a home
on the outskirts of Bayonne, the largest city in the French Basque
region.
   As they emerged about 1 a.m., they were confronted by the
gendarmes. Two of the Iparretarrak members, Joseph Etcheveste and
Pierre Aguerre, were wounded by gunfire and taken to the local
hospital for treatment. Etcheveste was described as Bidart's top
lieutenant.
   Bidart and the other two, Philippe Lascaray and Jean-Paul
Hiribaren, then surrendered.
   Defense Minister Andre Giraud sent a message of congratulations
to the Gendarmerie, saying the arrests were the result of a long
effort ``accomplished in particularly delicate and often dangerous
conditions.''
   Authorities said only one Iparretarrak member remained at large,
Lucienne, Fourcade, and they issued an appeal for her to surrender.
   ``No harm will be done to her. We known she never intended to
kill anyone,'' the Gendermerie in Bayonne said. ``She cannot stay
on the run by herself.''
   Bidart, 35, had been sought since Nov. 7, 1981, when he was
caught on camera during a bank robbery in Saint Paul les Dax, a
Basque country town.
   Bidart was convicted in absentia of murder in the March 19,
1982, slayings of two national policemen killed in St. Etienne de
Baigorry, his hometown. He received a life sentence in that case
and another life term for a conviction in absentia for the bank
robbery.
   Authorities say Bidart also is believed responsible for two
other attacks in which gendarmes died, one on Aug. 7, 1983, and the
other last August.
   During his six years in hiding, Bidart gave one press conference
in hiding and made one cassette recording played at the funeral of
an Iparretarrak member last June.
</TEXT>
