<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DemocraticResponse-Text     02-20 0705</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democratic Response-Text,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan-Budget, a0569</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the Democratic response,
delivered by House Budget Chairman William Gray of Pennsylvania, to
President Reagan's radio address on Saturday:
   Hello, this is Congressman Bill Gray, the chairman of the House
Budget Committee. Two days ago the President sent Congress his
budget request for fiscal year 1989. But this year something is
different. Everybody is shocked at the calm on Capitol Hill.
   People have gotten used to a set pattern: the budget comes up,
the battle lines are drawn, political bombs are dropped, the war
begins. This time people wonder why no bombs are being dropped.
What's different is the president's budget. The budget that arrived
on my desk on Thursday is more realistic than any of the other
seven the President has sent to Congress.
   In large measure, of course, this is due to the bipartisan
agreement between the administration and Congress at the budget
summit last fall. That agreement established specific limits for
the major areas of the budget, including defense spending and
domestic programs.
   It also committed us to an equally important objective: real,
permanent significant deficit reduction. The president's budget
appears to meet the summit guidelines, which is why we're not
seeing the kind of fireworks we've had in the past. Let's give
credit where it's due: in at least some areas the president has
recognized that Congress' priorities are also the priorities of the
American people.
   Instead of trying to cut aid to education by 28 percent, as he
did last year, the president is proposing a four percent increase
from the current funding level. Instead of trying to cut back on
the war on drugs, the president would increase spending by 13
percent. And to deal with AIDS, one of our most important health
problems, the president is asking for a 40 percent increase in
funds for AIDS research and education.
   But in other areas, this budget is out of line with America's
needs and America's values. For example, the president's budget
would spend more for homes in space than for the homeless here on
earth. In fact, funding for the proposed space station would be
almost $1 billion, but funding for the needs of the homeless would
be only $219 million, far less than the amount authorized by
Congress.
   The President and his representatives have indicated that this
year they want to avoid confrontational politics and acrimonious
exchanges, the kinds of things that in previous years led to budget
stalemate and huge deficits. Well, we can all agree with that. The
success of the budget summit and the prospect of continued
administration involvement will, I believe, demonstrate that
nothing is wrong with the budget process, nothing that can't be
fixed by cooperation and compromise on priorities and policies.
   We proved that the process wasn't the problem when, in seven to
eight weeks, with cooperation and compromise, we designed and
implemented a two-year budget agreement. The spirit and willingness
to compromise are the oil that makes the budget process work. We
know that the economy has improved recently. Inflation is down, and
unemployment, after rising to records in the long recession, is
back down to its 1979 level.
   But we Democrats are concerned about the future. We cannot rest
comfortably with economic gains built on a policy of borrow,
borrow, spend, spend. The deficit is a problem we cannot escape by
talking about process. Since 1980, our national debt has more than
doubled. By next January, it will be almost $2.8 trillion. That
works out to $11,400 for every man, woman and child in the United
States, and every year we have to pay the interest on that debt. We
have made major progress, but we still have a long way to go.
   If we maintain the bipartisan spirit that came out of the budget
summit, we can pass a budget that reduces the deficits and meets
the needs of this nation. And if we maintain the spirit of
conciliation that has been evidenced so far this year, we can make
the budget process work and build a brighter future for the next
generation, and an America with greater opportunity. This is
Congressman Bill Gray.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
