<DOCNO> AP880220-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-20-88 1453EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     02-20 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Break Up Anti-Government Demonstration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot squads Saturday hurled tear gas
at hundreds of anti-government demonstrators marching through a
fashionable downtown shopping district and calling for fairer
election rules.
   About 500 demonstrators took to the streets and clashed with
police after a large rally at a Roman Catholic cathedral. At least
two firebombs were thrown by demonstrators, who eventually were
scattered by tear gas.
   No arrests or injuries were reported.
   Kim Dae-jung, head of the opposition Party for Peace for
Democracy, held an overnight sit-in with about 150 supporters at
the party headquarters to protest the government's stand on
election rules.
   The demonstrations were called to protest proposed changes in
rules for electing members of the National Assembly, the country's
parliament. Elections are to be held in April.
   The government is proposing that one to three representatives be
elected from each district, based on population. Kim's supporters
want the law to allow for one elected member from each district,
regardless of population.
   The protesters also demonstrated against the Dec. 16 election of
Roh Tae-woo of the governing Democratic Justice Party. The
opposition contends the elections were rigged. The new president is
to be inaugurated on Thursday.
   Rally participants shouted, ``Down with military dictatorship!''
and ``We oppose seizing power through fraudulent election!''
   Kim said electing one representative from each district would
ensure democratic representation.
   He also called on the rival opposition Reunification Democratic
Party to endorse his formula, but he charged that the party had
made a secret deal to support the government's election formula.
   The government has held separate talks with the rival opposition
groups on reforming rules for the National Assembly elections. The
Reunification Democratic Party favors a formula of electing more
than one representative from each district.
   Roh was catapulted to power after the two rival opposition
groups split a majority of the votes during the Dec. 16 election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
