<1ST_LINE>u a AM-RacialTug-of-War Bjt   02-20 0872</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Racial Tug-of-War, Bjt,0898</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gang Warfare Enters White Neighborhoods, Minorities Charge Unfair
Treatment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When an innocent bystander in an affluent Los
Angeles neighborhood was killed in the crossfire of a gang
gunbattle, local merchants asked for more police protection and
quickly got it.
   The swift action following the Jan. 30 incident sparked protest
from many blacks and Hispanics, who charged that similar requests
from poorer minority neighborhoods fall on deaf ears.
   A week after the shooting local minority leaders publicized a
new study to support claims that police react more slowly to
emergencies in less affluent areas. Police Chief Darryl Gates
released a letter Friday from the study's author saying his
findings had been misconstrued.
   The racial tug-of-war intensified last weekend when an off-duty
black police officer was arrested as he stood on a street corner in
an upscale neighborhood with six black youths. The officer said his
group was conducting an informal ``sting'' operation to investigate
alleged police harassment.
   ``None of those kids did anything except stand on that corner
and be black _ and that was enough,'' said Hawthorne Police Sgt.
Don Jackson. Police said Jackson's group was blocking the sidewalk.
   Gang violence fueled by drug trafficking has been a reality for
years in the city's predominantly black and Hispanic southside
neighborhoods. Drive-by shootings are commonplace, with innocent
bystanders being killed by errant or ricocheting bullets.
   In one recent incident, a 67-year-old woman was killed in a
drive-by shooting while she sat in a wheelchair in the doorway of
her southside home.
   There were more than 300 gang-related murders in Los Angeles
County in 1987. That figure may rise to 450 this year as gangs
battle for control of the lucrative crack cocaine market, said
Michael Genelin, head of the district attorney's gang division.
   ``And that's not the way it should be. We should be able to live
normally,'' said Barbara Thomas, spokeswoman for the South Central
Organizing Committee, a group that claims a membership of 78,000
black families.
   Gang violence has begun to move into more affluent, mainly white
areas, illustrated by the Jan. 30 shooting of 27-year-old Karen
Toshima, who was caught in gang crossfire. She was killed in
Westwood Village, a popular theater and restaurant district.
   When police stepped up patrols in the area, hundreds of
southside residents demonstrated at LAPD headquarters, charging
that officials ignored daily death tolls in their communities.
   Minority leaders publicized a just-released study ordered by the
Police Commission and prepared by the Public Administration Service
in Virginia. The study showed that police responded more slowly to
crimes in poor areas than in the more affluent Westside and San
Fernando Valley, the leaders said.
   The Police Department then released a letter from Peter Bellmio,
the principal author of the nearly 200-page report, that stated his
findings had been misinterpreted.
   The letter said the actual conclusion was that the Police
Department takes too long to respond to emergencies and does not
significantly respond more rapidly in any of the city's
geographical areas.
   Bellmio said he was under contract not to comment publically
until March 8, when he makes a formal report to the police
commission.
   The deployment controversy has fanned other racial issues, such
as the alleged harassment that prompted Jackson to conduct his own
``sting.''
   In an effort to prove that LAPD officers were mistreating
blacks, Jackson and six friends gathered on a busy street corner in
Westwood, while an associate secretly videotaped the scene.
Officers arrested Jackson on a misdemeanor charge and rounded up
and frisked the others.
   Police defended the arrest, saying Jackson's group was blocking
the sidewalk, refused to move when requested by officers and was
dressed in attire similar to gang members'. Jackson was released on
his own recognizance pending a court hearing.
   More criticism of the police came Monday when the Rev. William
Johnson, of Curry Christian Methodist Episcopal Temple, complained
that when officers do patrol black neighborhoods, they come ``ready
to do combat.''
   Mayor Tom Bradley, who is black, signed an ordinance Wednesday
that provided for the hiring of 150 more officers, increasing the
force to its largest strength ever, 7,500 officers.
   ``We're determined to return this city to a drug-free, gang-free
atmosphere,'' the mayor said.
   ``I've been telling the people of this city that we need
hundreds more police officers,'' said Gates, the police chief. ``We
should focus on getting rid of the problems, and not on the
complicated subject of deployment.''
   Some criminal experts say more officers won't make a difference
in poor, crime-infested areas.
   ``Historically, there's a resentment to an excessive show of
force,'' said Garrett Capune, professor of criminology at the
University of Southern California and California State University.
   ``It has a racist overtone, you know; there seems to be more
crime because there's more officers,'' he said. ``It becomes a sort
of self-fulfilling prophecy.''
   ``I don't know what these criminologists are all about,''
snapped City Councilman Nate Holden, who represents a mainly black
district. ``These guys can sit in some classroom and think what
it's supposed to be like. But they haven't seen the real world. I
resent them.
   ``Let them come into the black community and see what it's
like.''
</TEXT>
