<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CustodyFlight     02-20 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Custody Flight,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mom Regains Son By Foiling Polish Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top pingpong player went to Poland and took her
son away from her ex-husband, then hid from Polish authorities
until she could sneak the boy into Sweden, a newspaper said
Saturday.
   ``I have gone through hell, and the child has gone through
hell,'' Kaisa Karlsson said in a telephone interview with The
Denver Post from Stockholm, where she and her son Michael arrived
Friday.
   ``Probably this night I can sleep,'' said Karlsson's father,
Bohdan Dawidowicz, also a top table tennis player, from his home in
suburban Aurora.
   Karlsson, 26, has been fighting since 1983 to win custody of
Michael from her Polish ex-husband, who was initially given custody
in Colorado and Polish courts. She got the Colorado ruling
reversed, but the Polish ruling stood and she took matters into her
own hands a week ago Saturday.
   She said she took her son away during her regular visit with him
in Warsaw, then hid in a series of homes, working her way from the
Warsaw suburbs to the port city of Gdansk, the Post reported.
   There they boarded a ferry for Sweden late Thursday.
   Karlsson wouldn't say exactly how she got her son past Polish
police, who were looking for him.
   ``There are just too many people who could get in trouble,'' she
said.
   Karlsson and Dawidowicz's battles with the Polish government
began shortly after Dawidowicz decided to live in the United States
in 1971 in the middle of an international table tennis tour.
   Three years later, after going back to Poland, they won
permission for the whole family to come to the United States. She
won tournament after tournament representing U.S. teams, and in
1978 became a U.S. citizen.
   In 1981, she married Mitchell Gaca, another Polish immigrant.
Michael was born later that year. They were divorced in 1983, with
custody initially given to Gaca.
   Karlsson battled back, but her travels on the table tennis
circuit worked against her and in 1985 her ex-husband returned to
Poland with their son.
   The same year, Karlsson introduced new evidence in her case and
was awarded custody by an Aurora court, but it was too late.
   Karlsson and her father said they were disillusioned by the U.S.
government's hands-off approach.
   The State Department refused to intervene, saying Polish law
applied since Gaca had gotten a Polish court to award him custody.
   Donna Sherman, a spokeswoman for the consular division of the
U.S. State Department, said there is not much the government can do
once a child is in another country's jurisdiction.
   ``We cannot do anything that violates the laws of that
country,'' she said. ``We can arrange for meetings, to try and
arrange some kind of conciliation, but we can't force it. We can't
act as attorneys.''
   Karlsson, who has since married a Swedish businessman, hopes to
visit the United States this summer but says that in the meantime
she and Michael will relax in Sweden.
   ``He needs a little rest. I think he'll be sticking around the
house,'' she said.
</TEXT>
