<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Acuff,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opry Star Honored On 50th Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roy Acuff, ``the king of country
music,'' celebrated his 50th anniversary on the Grand Ole Opry by
citing the fans of the long-running show.
   Acuff, 84, received a standing ovation Friday night when he
appeared on the stage to mark his golden anniversary on the live
program.
   ``This is a little special occasion for Roy Acuff,'' he told the
audience after singing his best-known song, ``The Wabash
Cannonball.''
   ``I'm proud to have lived to see this day,'' he said. ``You are
the ones who made Roy Acuff and the Grand Ole Opry. Have fun, I'm
going to.''
   Moments before, when the curtain went up and the crowd rose,
Acuff playfully told the audience, ``Sit down so I can sing.''
   He later sang his version of ``Blue Eyes Crying in the Rain,'' a
song Willie Nelson also turned into a hit.
   ``That was written for me by Fred Rose many, many years ago,''
Acuff told the audience, which included representatives of Rotary
International from 22 countries. ``Then Willie Nelson brought it
back. He did a good job with it.''
   Acuff also saluted his dobro player, Bashful Brother Oswald, who
also was celebrating his 50th anniversary on the show.
   ``We haven't had a fight yet,'' Acuff said.
   Other Opry stars joined in honoring Acuff, a fiddler who came
out of the East Tennessee hills to become the Opry's first genuine
singing star.
   ``That's a long time, folks,'' singer Del Reeves said about the
50 years of performing. ``I hope he's here another 50.''
   Singer Porter Wagoner called Acuff ``one of the grandest men in
country music.'' Singer Connie Smith dedicated her song ``Once a
Day'' to him.
   Johnny Cash and his wife, June Carter Cash, were to have
appeared on the show during a special segment honoring Acuff, but
canceled because both have the flu, Opry officials said.
   The pry bills itself as the longest running radio show still on
the air. It has never missed a broadcast since going on the air in
1925, meaning Acuff has been on the program for all but 13 years of
its existence.
