<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Heart-Children     02-20 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Heart-Children,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Child Heart Transplants Show Signs of Heart Disease, Other Trouble</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There are signs that child heart transplant
recipients develop atherosclerosis and also have a worse survival
rate than adults given new hearts, a transplant surgeon says.
   Dr. D. Glenn Pennington, chief of the cardiac replacement
service at St. Louis University Hospital in St. Louis, said he has
seen ``indications of development of atherosclerosis'' in child
transplant recipients, and ``it may become more of a trend.''
   Atherosclerosis is the thickening of the internal lining of the
blood vessels and the cause of coronary artery disease.
   As for survival rates, ``I think it is worse than adults,'' with
infection the leading cause of death among children, Pennington, a
specialist in the use of artificial devices and in pediatric
transplantation, said Friday at an international conference on
thoracic organ transplantion.
   He said children who have received transplants do not have worse
problems with organ rejection than adults. But he said there is an
increasing number of child transplants who need retransplantation
because of progressive failure of the organs they have been given.
   ``I don't know what that means, but my suspicion is that if we
transplant children in infancy we will probably have to
retransplant at some point again,'' Pennington said.
   There was encouraging news on transplants from a leader in
transplantation for extremely young infants, Dr. Leonard L. Bailey,
of Loma Linda University Medical Center in California, who said
some of his patients have exhibited an ``immune tolerance'' not
seen in adults.
   As a result, several of the young recipients need only extremely
small doses of the anti-rejection drug cyclosporine and may be
withdrawn entirely from all drug therapy.
   ``My guess is that a number of the babies will be able to grow
up without the need for immunosuppression,'' Bailey said.
   Cyclosporine is used in transplantation in combination with
other drugs to suppress the body's immune system and keep it from
turning against the donor heart.
   Bailey said he believes the optimal therapy is diagnosis ``of
heart disease in-utero, because that gives us a chance then from 35
weeks on to find a donor.''
   He said that in his program's experience, transplants after more
than the first few weeks of a child's life make for a ``much more
difficult post-operative management problems. ... Those who have
been transplanted in the first month of life have really been a
piece of cake.''
   Infants more than 3 to 3{ months old given transplants ``will
reject with considerable vigor,'' requiring aggressive
anti-rejection therapy, said Bailey, who has performed heart
transplants on the world's youngest infants, including a
four-hour-old Canadian boy last October.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880220-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-20-88 1519EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Heart-Animals     02-20 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Heart-Animals,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Goats, Sheep, Primates' Examined as Possible Source of Human
Donor Hearts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The surgeon who transplanted a baboon's
heart into an infant girl in 1984 says he's optimistic about the
continuing research toward eventual use of animal heart transplants
in humans.
   ``We're still really working vigorously in that area from all
points of view, goats and sheep and primates,'' Dr. Leonard L.
Bailey said at a three-day international conference on thoracic
organ transplantation that concluded Saturday.
   Researchers have turned to exploring the use of non-human organs
for transplantation on either a temporary or possibly permanent
basis, in part because of the lack of sufficient organ donors.
   In a controversial procedure in October 1984, Bailey and his
staff at Loma Linda University Medical Center transplanted the
heart of a baboon into a 12-day-old girl known as Baby Fae.
   The child, born with a fatal heart defect, survived for 20 days
before her body's immune system rejected the foreign-tissue
transplant, or xenograft.
   Rejection has been a major obstacle in xenografts.
   Another problem area has been the ethical question of using a
primate heart in humans, said Dr. Bartley P. Griffith, of the
University of Pittsburgh.
   Griffith, thoracic and cardiovascular surgeon at one of the
nation's busiest transplant centers, said chimpanzees ``are almost
too close'' to humans in terms of behavior and would raise a moral
dilemma.
   ``Nobody is talking about using chimpanzees, and yet they in
fact are the most size-appropriate probably to use,'' he said.
   Griffith added that baboons' hearts are small for human use and
might eventually be used more appropriately as auxiliary hearts.
   Bailey said the testing that has been conducted at the Loma
Linda, Calif., facility has involved a series of experiments,
testing the ``xenograft bridge to allograft theory, and it's
working out very well.'' An allograft is a same-species organ
transplant.
   The testing, he said, includes using xenografts of green monkey
hearts into baboons in temporary bridge-to-transplant situations.
   ``We still very firmly believe that a well-selected primate
heart from a baboon will be virtually as good'' as a human
allograft ``that may have no tissue match whatsoever and bear very
little resemblance and genetic makeup'' to the original _ even as a
permanent graft, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880220-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-20-88 1522EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Farming     02-20 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Farming,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rockefeller Foundation Set Up For Polish Farmers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American banker and philanthropist David
Rockefeller unveiled a private non-profit foundation Saturday that
he said will aid hard-pressed farmers in this communist country.
   Rockefeller met privately with Polish communist leader Gen.
Wojciech Jaruzelski before formally inaugurating the foundation,
which will raise pigs and export hams to the United States.
   ``It seems to me that what we all need to do is to find ways in
which despite the ideological differences, we can work together,''
Rockefeller said at a ceremony in Warsaw's Royal Castle.
   Organizers said the foundation brings Poland its first new
long-term Western credits since the 1981 martial law crackdown and
will serve as a model for Western institutions wishing to provide
financial assistance to the debt-stricken country.
   But the size of the credits, $2.4 million, is miniscule compared
to Poland's burgeoning foreign debt, now standing at $39.2 billion.
   The Foundation for the Development of Polish Agriculture is the
result of the personal interest of Rockefeller and the Rockefeller
Brothers' Fund, said Leon Irish, chairman of the foundation's
organizing committee.
   Its first project will be the development of swine production to
increase exports of premium Polish hams to the United States by 14
percent.
   The foundation will borrow money to import to Poland
high-protein feed concentrates from the United States for sale to
Polish farmers under a contract arrangement.
   The farmers will use the feed to raise swine more efficiently.
The swine will be sold to Polish meat processors in partnership
with the foundation.
   Hams resulting from the arrangement will be exported to the
United States, with a portion staying in Poland for domestic sale.
   Proceeds from the exports will repay foreign loans and be used
for other foundation projects, Irish said.
   Unlike other East bloc nations where cooperative farming
predominates, private farmers control 75 percent of the farmland in
Poland and produce 80 percent of the crop.
   The foundation is to be governed by a council with 60 percent
U.S. and Western European membership and 40 percent private Polish
membership.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880220-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-20-88 1531EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--EMSDelay     02-20 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--EMS Delay,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EMS: Crew Delayed Rescue for Food</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two city ambulance workers face disciplinary
charges because they waited for their sandwiches in a delicatessen
before responding to a report of a heart attack victim 1{ blocks
away, officials said Saturday.
   The man died in the incident Wednesday in the Bronx.
   The Emergency Medical Service said its investigation had
substantiated allegations of delay. Both crew members had been
reassigned to clerical duties and faced disciplinary charges, it
said.
   EMS director James Kerr said it was impossible to know whether
the delay, which he said amounted to 5 minutes, had cost the
stricken man his life. But he said EMS policy requires ambulance
crews to respond immediately.
   The crew had just ordered sandwiches to go when a man ran in
into the deli at 8:30 p.m. Wednesday and said someone had suffered
a heart attack in the Church of the Mediator, Kerr said.
   Instead of leaving at once, the investigation showed, the pair
waited for their sandwiches, Kerr said. He declined to identify the
crew or discuss possible penalties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
