<1ST_LINE>r a AM-UMassTakeover     02-20 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UMass Takeover,0682</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sit-in Looked Unpromising, Leaders Said</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sit-in launched by 200 University of
Massachusetts students at the start of a snowy holiday weekend
seemed doomed by doubt and disarray, leaders of the little
rebellion by minorities recalled.
   ``You do not take a building on a night before a major snowstorm
that will close it anyway and which is going to be closed for an
entire holiday weekend,'' Michael Thelwell, a black professor, said
he warned the protesters at the start of the occupation.
   But by the end of the six-day occupation of New Africa House,
hundreds of white students had displayed their sympathy in rallies
and vigils, money and supplies had poured in from around the nation
and even the chancellor had expressed admiration for the
protesters, who won several concessions from the school.
   ``We weren't organized. All we had were these five little
demands,'' said Jo Ella Costello, a negotiator for the group. ``But
something had brought us all together. That was the fascinating
thing. By the third day, we knew it was working.''
   The takeover began Feb. 11 after students met with Chancellor
Joseph D. Duffey to discuss the demands. Troubled by recent acts of
racial violence on campus, the protesters insisted on the
disciplining of five white students accused of beating two blacks,
and they demanded a stop to the encroachment of other school
departments on New Africa House, a Third World center.
   Tension had festered since an October 1986 beating of a black
student by several whites following the Boston Red Sox loss to the
New York Mets in the final game of the World Series.
   The disorganized protesters refused to meet with Duffey the
morning after the takeover, but began forming committees to handle
finances, security, media questions and negotiations, and they
imposed strict procedures on meetings.
   The rules proved successful. ``We started voting on everything,'
Costello said. ``We even voted on which movies to watch.''
   Support began pouring in from the campus and beyond. The Black
Faculty Senate said members would risk arrest with the protesters
if the chancellor called in police to remove them from the
building, Costello said.
   The Massachusetts Teachers Association volunteered to strike in
the same event, she said. Some 500 white students staged a rally
outside the building to lend their support.
   Costello said she knew the protesters had won widespread support
when she went to a nearby dormitory for a shower: ``They said, `You
all from New Africa House?' I said, `Yeah. Anybody got any soap?'
They ran to get it. They'd give us deodorant, anything.''
   Costello was among four women and five men elected by the
protesters to negotiate with the chancellor.
   A meeting scheduled for Monday had to be postponed when Duffey
went to visit a brother who had undergone major surgery. The
protesters sent the chancellor a card and Duffey responded with a
basket of fruit.
   ``We had old-timers with us saying, `My god, I've been going to
sit-ins for 20 years and I've never seen anything like this,''
Costello said.
   Duffey and the students met Tuesday and talked for more than
four hours.
   But then the group that had been occupying the house was
suddenly outnumbered by minorities returning to the campus from the
holiday weekend.
   ``They were acting like we'd sold out,'' saidCostello.
   ``I was really hurt by all these people who hadn't been there
the whole time. I asked them, `Where were you?'''
   The newcomers left early Wednesday and the stalwart core voted
to accept Duffey's responses to their demands, which included
timetables for the hiring of minority faculty and a promise to
leave the New Africa House in the hands of the Third World
community.
   Costello said the agreement was a victory that will enhance the
school's image among whites and blacks.
   ``I think UMass will get the reputation of fighting racism,''
she said. ``This is terrific, what's happening here.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
