<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Estonia 1stLd-Writethru a0536 02-20 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Estonia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0536,0689</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Estonian Government Blasts U.S. Senators</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 5 grafs to UPDATE with expelled Estonian political
activist and family arriving in Sweden.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Shultz, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government in Estonia accused U.S. senators of
trying to ruin Soviet-American relations and scuttle nuclear
disarmament by encouraging nationalist demonstrations in the Baltic
republic, Tass said Saturday.
   The official Soviet news agency said the Presidium of the
Supreme Soviet of Estonia issued a statement saying the senators
are ``taking part in a new propaganda farce. They advocate a
favorable attitude to anti-Soviet actions planned to be held in
Estonia by some groups.''
   ``Such steps can further only one political aim _ to hamper the
improvement of Soviet-American relations and to undermine the
nuclear disarmament process,'' Tass said.
   The statement was the latest manifestation of a dispute between
the government and nationalist activists, supported by Western
politicians, over the fate of the Baltic states.
   The states, Estonia, Lithuania and Latvia, were independent
until they were incorporated into the Soviet Union in 1940. Some
residents believe their national identity and religious freedom are
suppressed under Soviet rule.
   Moscow-based dissidents said some Lithuanians demonstrated
Tuesday to celebrate the 70th anniversary of the declaration of
independence from Soviet Russia months after the Bolshevik
revolution of 1917. Wednesday is Estonia's anniversary of
independence, and activists say they plan protests there also.
   This month, 32 U.S. senators wrote to Kremlin leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev asking him not to interfere with demonstrations and
religious services in the Baltics. The senators urged Gorbachev
``not only to allow the Lithuanian and Estonian people to
peacefully honor their national independence days, but also to take
all necessary measures to guarantee that they do not become targets
of state-sponsored harassment.''
   Estonia's Presidium shot back that ``those who call into
question the choice made by Estonia in 1940, when it joined the
Union of Soviet Socialists Republics as a full-fledged member,
oppose the will of our people, the policy of perestroika, the
principles of humanism and the policy of peace.''
   Perestroika is the name of Gorbachev's wide-ranging program to
reform Soviet society.
   In a speech to the Communist Party Central Committee on
Thursday, Gorbachev acknowledged the nationalities problem remains
thorny. He said Soviets must respect the language and culture of
national groups but that nationalism aimed at ``self-isolation lead
only to a spiritual blind alley.''
   The Presidium statement also acknowledged the nationalities
problem, but said some people are taking advantage of the recent
Soviet campaign for openness ``as a means of kindling hostility
among the nationalities living on Estonian territory. This fully
applies to the groups that emerged in Estonia which try to put
Soviet Estonia and its history in a bad light.''
   Tass did not say when the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet of
Estonia, the republic's nominal parliament, issued the statement.
   Last August, thousands of people demonstrated in Estonia's
capital and those of the other Baltic states on the anniversary of
a secret agrement between Nazi Germany and the Soviet Union the led
to the Soviet takeover of the Baltic states in 1940.
   The U.S. government has never recognized the Soviet
incorporation of the Baltic states.
   In a related development, an Estonian political activist and his
family of six arrived in Sweden Saturday after being expelled from
the Soviet Union.
   About 30 exiles greeted Rein Metz, his wife and five small
children at the airport.
   Metz told Swedish television at Stockholm's Arlanda airport he
was the leader of a ``religious and political association.'' He
said he expected ``30-40'' more members of his congregation could
be forced to leave.
   ``I greet you in the name of Jesus,'' he told some 30 exiles at
the airport.
   Last weekend two converted Estonian Buddhists arrived in Sweden
after given the choice of going to jail or leave the country. One
of them, Eke-Part Nomm, 22, said he had probably been forced to
leave because he read an appeal to form an Estonian Independence
Party at a meeting in the city of Tartu on Feb. 2.
</TEXT>
