<1ST_LINE>d a AM-LabFire     02-20 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lab Fire,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leading Maple Research Lab Destroyed In Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNDERHILL, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire officials and University of Vermont
researchers Saturday picked through the rubble of a nationally
known laboratory for maple tree research destroyed by fire.
   The laboratory at the university-affiliated Proctor Maple
Research Farm was engulfed in flames Friday night in a fire of
undetermined origin, university officials said.
   Frederick Laing, an associate professor long involved in
research at the farm, said efforts in recent years had centered on
finding a cause for declines in maple syrup production in Vermont
and around the Northeast.
   Much of that research had been looking into whether acid
precipitation, atmospheric pollutants carried into the Northeast on
winds out of the Midwest, was to blame for recent maple production
declines.
   Laing said Saturday that it was now ``generally agreed that it
(acid rain) is one of the stresses'' causing the slump in maple
sugaring. ``There's still some difficulty in assessing just how
large a part it plays.''
   The fire, which Laing said destroyed between $200,000 and
$250,000 worth of equipment, comes with this year's maple sugar
season about a month away. It was unclear Saturday whether the lab
or some replacement facility could be geared up in time.
   Rayburn Levigne, a UVM assistant vice president for buildings
and facilities, said while the cause of the fire was unknown, it
was not believed to have been arson.
</TEXT>
