<DOCNO> AP880220-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-20-88 1619EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deer-Culverts     02-20 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deer-Culverts,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deer Snub Tunnels Meant to Protect Them From Busy Highways</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEB RIECHMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FROSTBURG, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Possibly spooked by light at the end of
the tunnel, deer have been shy about using four passageways
recently installed for them under a new Maryland interstate highway.
   The State Highway Administration built four corrugated steel
culverts under sections of Interstate 97 near Annapolis in hopes of
encouraging animals to cross under instead of over the roadway.
   Researchers at the University of Maryland's Appalachian
Environmental Laboratory in Frostburg are trying to find out if
animals are using the underpasses. So far they've found mink, mice,
muskrat and raccoon, but no deer have ventured through the dimly
lighted pathways.
   ``To us, the opening (at the other end) looks fairly large,''
said William R. Gates, a graduate assistant working on the project.
``But for deer, it's like going into a cave or tunnel and they
aren't used to going into enclosures.''
   Several other states have tried culverts, but little has been
done to document their use.
   The state and federal highway administrations are funding the
$210,000, five-year study in hopes of finding a way to reduce the
number of animals killed on American highways.
   According to the Federal Highway Administration, an estimated
200,000 deer die each year on U.S. roads. However, Doug Smith, an
FHA ecologist, said the number was a conservative estimate. More
than 25,000 are killed each year on roads in states with high deer
populations, such as Pennsylvania.
   The study also aims to learn more about what happens to a
wildlife area when it is bisected by a highway. The interstate cuts
through woods near Crownsville State Hospital.
   Researchers are observing tracks and using a wildlife
surveillance system to monitor animal activity in the culverts.
Movement at the tunnel openings trips sensors on video cameras,
which film the activity day or night.
   ``So far we had a deer enter the culvert and then come back
out,'' Gates said.
   Recent flooding inside the tunnels might have discouraged some
animals from using them, but Gates said he suspected the culverts
might not be large enough.
   Three of the culverts are 15 feet high, 21 feet wide and about
as long as a football field. The fourth is even longer, at more
than 500 feet. Perhaps the deer assume they cannot get through what
they perceive is a tiny opening at the other end, Gates said.
   ``The only evidence I have is that we have had several deer
approach the culverts, but they have not gone in,'' he said.
   If the culverts prove successful, they would be a cheaper than
bridges, which cost four to five times more to build and maintain,
said William L. Branch, environmental specialist with Maryland's
highway administration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
