<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-NorthKorea     02-20 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-North Korea,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan Communist Party Accuses North Korea Of Bombing Airliner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By K.P. HONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Japan Communist Party has accused communist
North Korea of bombing a South Korean airliner that vanished with
115 aboard off the coast of Burma last November.
   The party, in an official publication obtained Saturday by The
Associated Press, stressed that communism has nothing to do with
terrorism and that true communists should denounce such violence.
   ``We firmly believe that the north actually did it,'' wrote
party Central Committee Chairman Kenji Miyamoto in the publication.
   North Korea has denied any involvement in the jet's
disappearance, and accused Seoul of engineering the incident to
malign Pyongyang.
   The Korean Air Boeing 707, on its way from the Middle East to
Seoul, disappeared on Nov. 29.
   On Jan. 15, a woman said in a public confession in Seoul that
she was a North Korean agent and that she and a male North Korean
agent had planted a bomb on the aircraft during an earlier leg of
the plane's flight.
   The woman, identified as Kim Hyon Hui, 26, said Kim Jong Il, son
and heir apparent of North Korean President Kim Il Sung, had
ordered the sabotage because he wanted to disrupt the 1988 Summer
Olympics, to begin in Seoul Sept. 17.
   The North Korean pair, traveling on forged Japanese passports,
left the plane in Abu Dhabi, its last stop before it vanished, flew
to Bahrain and were stopped for questioning at Bahrain Airport on
Dec. 1. Both swallowed poison before being questioned. The man died
but the woman survived. She was extradited to Seoul on Dec. 15.
   Japanese communists have been at odds with North Korean
communist leaders since the early 1970s over ideological
differences, often denouncing the personality cult surrounding Kim
Il Sung and Jong Il.
</TEXT>
