<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     02-20 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DIXON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The people of Dixon are reading about life in
Dickson, Siberia, thanks to the efforts of Mayor James Dixon and
his Soviet counterpart.
   This week, Dixon received 100 copies of the Dickson newspaper
``Sovetsky Taimyr,'' printed in English. Ordinarily, the daily
newspaper is printed only in Russian.
   ``We want this issue to link us like a bridge over the cold
ocean that lies between us. We want you to see ... that not so many
things divide us after all,'' editor-in-chief Albion Brechalov
wrote in a front-page story.
   The friendship between the two cities began in January, when the
mayor of Dickson, Siberia, sent New Year's greetings to the people
of Dixon, Ill.
   Mayor Dixon replied, suggesting a citizen exchange visit, and he
announced earlier this month that he had been notified that
Dickson's mayor, an interpreter and a journalist will visit Dixon
for a week, though no date has been set.
   The Dickson newspaper tries to show everyday life in that
Siberian city, which is roughly a third the size of Dixon, a
community of 15,000 in north-central Illinois. On the front page of
the newspaper, dated November 1987, is a picture of three bundled
woman eating ice cream bars.
   Half of the newspaper contains carefully written letters from
citizens expressing friendship and a hope for world peace. Some
also expressed opposition to the policies of President Reagan, who
spent his boyhood and high school years in Dixon.
   Mayor Dixon says he is sending Dickson 19 large photographs,
taken by local amateurs, that show life in Dixon.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is sending tortilla-grams to
remind illegal aliens that the deadline to apply for immigration
amnesty is less than three months away.
   ``We're trying anything we can think of to get people the
information,'' said Jane Friday, an Immigration and Naturalization
Service spokeswoman.
   The INS has printed 80,000 Spanish-language reminders on
4-by-6-inch pieces of paper, and next week plans to send them to
tortilla factories in Brownfield, Odessa and Lovington, N.M., where
they will be stuffed into packages.
   ``We have had lots of publicity in larger areas. The purpose of
this grass-roots publicity campaign is to get out the word in the
smaller areas,'' Ms. Friday said.
   The text of the inserts says: ``Act now. Take advantage of the
legalization program. Amnesty ends May 4, 1988. If you have lived
in the United States illegally since before Jan. 1, 1982, perhaps
you qualify. For peace of mind, legalize your status. For more
information, please contact your local legalization office.''
   The bakeries agreed to include the reminders in their tortilla
packages as a public service and at no charge to the government,
Ms. Friday said.
   The INS has been using more traditional outlets _ churches,
schools and public service broadcasts _ to remind people in
metropolitan areas that the government's amnesty offer expires May
4.
</TEXT>
