<FILEID>AP-NR-02-20-88 1635EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-HumanRights     02-20 0709</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Human Rights,0725</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Would-be Emigrants Get New Refusals on Eve of Shultz Visit</BYLINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Shultz, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yuri and Tanya Zieman got bad news again last
week. Their latest application for an exit visa was turned down by
Soviet authorities.
   Vladimir Tufeld learned Friday that he, too, had once more been
refused.
   Their disappointment was aggravated by the timing, for the
latest rejection notices arrived on the eve of Secretary of State
George Shultz's visit to Moscow, an event many Jewish
``refuseniks'' had hoped would help get them out.
   In the past, the Soviets often have lowered emigration barriers
just before high-level U.S.-Soviet talks, but there is no
indication Shultz's scheduled arrival on Sunday has had much effect.
   ``People are pinning so many hopes on him that I'm afraid it's
going to be a very pathetic frustration for many,'' Mrs. Zieman
said. ``There is nothing to pin your hopes on now.''
   A senior Western diplomat who watches trends in Soviet
emigration and other human rights matters, said, ``What had been
some fairly steady but limited improvement (last year) may have
come to a halt.''
   As for freeing of political prisoners, ``the process has
stopped'' following the release last year of dozens of religious,
humans rights and nationalist activists, the diplomat said. He
spoke only on condition he not be identified.
   Observers say one possible reason the flow of Jewish emigrants
appears to have slowed from last year's unusually high levels is
that the issue is receiving less official and public attention now.
   Most of the best-known ``refuseniks'' have left in recent
months, said one diplomatic analyst, and although thousands of
would-be emigrants are left behind, they aren't as well organized
and don't have as effective a voice as some of the Jewish activists
who have recently been granted exit visas.
   The Ziemans first applied for permission to emigrate when their
daughter, Vera, was a baby. Vera is now 11 years old and has grown
up knowing she and her family could leave at any time. But while
they wait, they are outcasts.
   Yuri Zieman, 50, lost his job as a computer programmer in the
biomedical field as soon as he applied to leave and worked until
recently as a janitor. The family's plight has taken on a new
urgency since Yuri suffered a potentially deadly aneurysm in the
brain several weeks ago and doctors warned him not to risk the
delicate surgery to repair the afflicted artery unless he can reach
the West.
   Although Zieman says he never had access to state secrets, the
only reason he and his family have been given for the authorities'
refusal to permit them to leave is that theirs is a ``security''
case.
   Tufeld's wife, Isolda, was granted a three-month visa in
December to enable her to have surgery for a brain tumor. She
remains in Johns Hopkins University Hospital in Baltimore, Md.,
after undergoing three operations last month, her husband said
Saturday.
   Jewish emigration reached a peak of about 51,000 in 1979, but
dropped after that as U.S.-Soviet relations worsened. In 1986,
fewer than 1,000 were allowed to emigrate. The number rose above
8,000 last year for the first time since 1979 but appears to have
reached a plateau or declined since the U.S.-Soviet summit in
December in Washington.
   Some refuseniks blame Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
public annoyance at being questioned repeatedly on the subject.
Others fear the U.S. government has lost some of its persistence in
the drive to improve relations and reach a strategic nuclear
weapons accord with the Kremlin.
   In the meantime, new groups of Jews are forming to press their
exit demands.
   One, calling itself the New Wave, announced it will hold
demonstrations every week in downtown Moscow to protest the refusal
of Soviet authorities to recognize its members' eligibility for
visas because they acknowledge they don't have immediate relatives
abroad.
   Another group, called the Second Generation, consists of young
people whose parents have spent years trying unsuccessfully to
leave the country. The children, many now in their teens or 20s,
have grown up expecting that one day they would go to the West with
their parents but now find they are barred, just as their parents
were.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
