<FILEID>AP-NR-02-20-88 1715EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Politics     02-20 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Politics,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Center-Left Party Endorses Mitterrand For Re-Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The small Left Radical Movement party said Saturday
it was endorsing Socialist President Francois Mitterrand for
re-election, even though he hasn't declared himself a candidate.
   The center-left party, which has two members in the 577-seat
National Assembly, decided at its national convention to support
Mitterrand in the April 24 election, said party spokesman Emile
Zuccarelli.
   ``The possibility that Mr. Mitterrand will not be a candidate is
so unlikely that it wasn't even worth our considering,'' Zuccarelli
told reporters.
   The Socialists, by far the strongest leftist party, are waiting
for Mitterrand to announce his decision before making an
endorsement. He is expected to make his plans known in the middle
of March and is expected to be a candidate.
   Public opinion polls indicate Mitterrand has far more popular
support than the best-known declared candidates _ Premier Jacques
Chirac and former Premier Raymond Barre. The two conservatives are
running neck-and-neck for second place.
   Other declared candidates include Jean-Marie Le Pen of the
extreme-right National Front, Andre Lajoinie of the Communists and
Pierre Juquin, a dissident Communist. None is given much chance of
making the runoff, which will be held May 8 between the top two
vote-getters unless one candidate wins more than 50 percent April
24.
   The Radical Movement was France's leading party before World War
II, with a progressive, anti-clerical program. It has gradually
lost strength, and it split in the 1970s into the Left Radicals and
the center-right Valoisian Radicals, who participate in Chirac's
coalition government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880220-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-20-88 1715EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     02-20 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Places Units On Full Alert Around Manila Following
Killings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military chief of staff put all
troops and police in the Manila area on full alert Saturday to
prevent disruption of second anniversary celebrations of President
Corazon Aquino's rise to power.
   Gen. Renato de Villa said he also placed the alert after the
killings of at least six people on Manila streets in the past two
weeks, the government-run Philippine News Agency reported.
   Authorities have blamed the ambushes and slayings on communist
guerillas.
   De Villa also ordered the arrest Saturday of a navy captain
linked to the 1986 murder of a leftist labor leader, but the
officer refused to leave his home, saying the arrest papers were
not in order.
   De Villa canceled all military leaves and ordered his troops to
intensify patrols and set up nighttime mobilecheckpoints, the
agency said.
   The celebrations next week mark the Feb. 26, 1986
civilian-military coup that placed Mrs. Aquino in power after
ousting President Ferdinand Marcos, who now lives in exile in
Hawaii.
   The military said earlier this month that it uncovered plans by
communist rebels to step up slayings in the Manila area this year.
More than 130 policemen and soldiers were killed in the capital
last year.
   Military field reports reaching Manila Saturday said at least
six communist New People's Army guerrillas were killed and one
soldier wounded in clashes Friday in Surigao del Norte and Bukidnon
provinces on the southern island of Mindanao.
   In Cebu City, 350 miles southeast of Manila, police said they
discovered Friday the bodies of five people who they believed were
executed by rebels on suspicion of being military informers.
   Navy Capt. Rex Robles meanwhile denied involvement in the
November 1986 murder of leftist labor leader Rolando Olalia and
refused to accompany arresting officers because they carried only a
photocopy of de Villa's arrest order, Robles' lawyer told reporters.
   In the order, de Villa said Robles was being arrested ``in
connection'' with the slaying of the charismatic chairman of the
May 1st Movement, one of the Philippines' largest labor federations.
   Attorney Armando Marcelo told reporters that Robles challenged
the government to present evidence of his involvement.
   The arresting officers left Robles' guarded home after he
refused to go with them, Marcelo said.
</TEXT>
