<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-Ortega 1stLd-Writethru a0629 02-20 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Ortega, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0629,0627</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan President Warns Opposition Against Insurrection</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 13th graf ``Although the...'' to ADD
other currency measures. Pickup 14th graf pvs ``Groups from...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Central America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega said Saturday
that the right, the extreme left and the opposition newspaper La
Prensa should ``be careful, because they can in fact provoke an
insurrection that can destroy them.''
   Speaking at the closing of the leftist government's meeting on
new economic measures, Ortega said ``enemies of the revolution,''
including the political opposition, the U.S. government and La
Prensa, opposed new economic steps announced by his administration
the past week.
   He called La Prensa ``the daily of the CIA.''
   The opposition from both sides of the political spectrum and the
Superior Council of Private Enterprise, Ortega said, ``have said
that the time for an insurrection has come.''
   He said they should not ``be looking for five feet on the cat
because they may find them. They should be careful, because if they
put themselves on the side of the Contras and the aggressors they
are going to stir winds that can provoke tempests.''
   The Superior Council of Private Enterprise is the most important
private business organization in Nicaragua.
   Adding more teeth to the economic measures announced earlier,
Ortega announced one- to four-year prison sentences for
speculators. He said taxi drivers and others who work in
transportation would have their vehicles confiscated if they
charged more than the official prices.
   He also announced a 10 percent reduction in the national budget
and a tax exemption for 22,900 families whose housing loans were
forgiven by the government.
   The exact amount of the budget is not known and he did not
elaborate on where the cuts would be made.
   Those and other measures announced the past week are ``to give
the economy a push and fight inflation,'' he said.
   The Sandinista government on Monday created a new cordoba
currency worth 1,000 times as much as the old one and pegged it at
10 to the dollar.
   It also raised salaries to five times what they were in December
and authorized price increases of up to more than 50 percent on
some basic goods.
   Although the measures were designed to slow inflation, which was
1,500 percent for 1987, prices already were being hiked beyond the
new official levels.
   Ortega issued a decree that requires individuals and
corporations to report any foreign currency holdings of more than
$500.
   A stamped, signed copy of a report of the holdings to one of the
country's banks will be legal authorization for the owner to keep
the money, said the decree issued Friday. Reports must be filed
within 15 days but are not required if the funds are deposited in
state-owned banks.
   Failure to follow the rules will be considered a currency
violation, punishable by one to three years in prison under a 1981
law.
   Another decree authorizes the government's Central Bank to
investigate large deposits of old cordobas if there are suspected
of being linked to illegal activity.
   Groups from Sandinista Defense Committees, civilian neighborhood
organizations, accompanied by police, have raided storerooms of
alleged black market businesses and public markets to confiscate
goods and force vendors to sell at official prices.
   Ortega compared the economic measures to ``a strong medicine''
for a sick person.
   ``As long as the war doesn't end, we are going to try to have
the patient recover to better confront the aggressor,'' he said.
   The Contra rebels, which have been supported by the U.S.
government, have been fighting more than six years to overthrow the
Sandinistas.
</TEXT>
