<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TrappedRobber     02-20 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trapped Robber,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moonlighting Roofer Caught in Bank's Air Vent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YVETTE BLACKMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLIP, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A roofer who apparently was trying to break
into a bank by shimmying down an air vent was trapped upside-down
in the vent for five hours Saturday, police said.
   Raymond Mention of Bayshore suffered minor injuries to his right
arm and collar bone and bruises on his face, said Officer Thomas
Sorriano, a Suffolk County police spokesman.
   ``This is the first time in my life I've ever been so glad to
see a bunch of cops,'' Mention told his rescuers.
   Employees of the Long Island Savings Bank in Islip arrived at
work at 8:45 a.m. and heard a man calling for help, Sorriano said.
   When the officers reached the roof, they found a roofer's belt
and tools, the vent, and then discovered Mention's feet ``wiggling
up in the air,'' said Officer Mark Ryan.
   ``He told them he tried to get in feet first and when he
couldn't, he tried head first,'' Ryan said. ``He had nothing to
hold on to and fell in.''
   The officers kept Mention talking while they tried to get the
blood circulating in his legs and pry him from the curve in the
2-foot-by-2-foot vent where he had become lodged, he said.
   When he was finally freed, Mention asked for the time, was told
it was 9 a.m., and said he had been stuck for five hours, Ryan said.
   Mention was taken to Southside Hospital, where he was treated
and released into police custody. The roofer was charged with
criminal mischief; other charges were pending, said Sorriano.
Arraignment was scheduled for Sunday.
</TEXT>
