<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Seydell     02-20 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Seydell,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Journalist Mildred Seydell Dies At 98</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mildred Seydell, a globe-trotting journalist who
interviewed Benito Mussolini and covered the Scopes ``monkey
trial,'' died Saturday. She was 98.
   Ms. Seydell, a resident of the suburban Atlanta town of Roswell,
once said she ``much preferred to set the stage for adventure
rather than the table for dinner.'' Her work as a writer and
columnist for Hearst publications, including the now-defunct
Atlanta Georgian newspaper, took her around the world.
   She wrote ``Talks With Celebrities,'' including an interview
with the Italian dictator Mussolini, for Universal News Service and
27 Hearst papers. She also covered for Hearst the 1925 Tennessee
trial of John Scopes, a teacher indicted for illegally teaching the
theory of evolution.
   Ms. Seydell was a columnist for the Atlanta Georgian from 1926
to 1939, the year the paper closed.
   Born Mildred Woolley in Atlanta, she married Paul Seydel, a
chemist she met while studying at the Sorbonne in Paris, in 1910.
She added an ``l'' to Seydel and adopted the name for her writing.
   She is survived by two sons, grandchildren and
great-grandchildren.
</TEXT>
