<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Angola-Rebels     02-20 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola-Rebels,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNITA Reports Killing 17 Enemy Soldiers; Shooting Down MIG-23</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angola's UNITA rebels said Saturday they
killed 16 enemy soldiers in recent fighting and shot down a fighter
plane, killing a Cuban pilot.
   UNITA, the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola,
said in a statement distributed in Lisbon that guerrillas killed 14
Angolan soldiers and two Cubans in an attack Feb. 12 on two army
battalions close to the strategic southern town of Cuito Cuanavale.
   The rebels, supported by the United States and South Africa,
said guerrilla anti-aircraft guns shot down a Soviet-built MIG-23
fighter jet the same day, killing the Cuban pilot.
   UNITA also claimed rebels ambushed a train and destroyed the
locomotive during the first two weeks of February between the towns
of Catete and Botomona in central Luanda province.
   The guerrillas said they had also captured the town of Luquembo
and two army garrisons in cenetral Malange province.
   The statement gave rebel casualties in recent fighting as two
killed and nine wounded.
   UNITA has been fighting to force Angola's Soviet- and
Cuban-backed government to share power since 1975, when Angola
gained independence from Portugal.
</TEXT>
