<1ST_LINE>r i AM-IRAArrest 1stLd-Writethru a0575 02-20 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IRA Arrest, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0575,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Extradition Ordered for Captured IRA Activist; Haughey Welcomes
Limits</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with Irish Prime Minister welcoming
extradition limits with Britain, quotes, details, background.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SLIGO, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court Saturday ordered the extradition
of a prominent Irish Republican Army activist to Northern Ireland.
Prime Minister Charles Haughey, citing a separate case, welcomed
limits on extraditions to Britain.
   Owen Carron, 34, a former member of the British Parliament and a
leading member of Sinn Fein, the IRA's legal political wing, had
been sought since he jumped bail on a weapons charge in Northern
Ireland two years ago.
   Police arrested him Friday night in the southwestern county of
Sligo, about 20 miles from the Northern Ireland border, after an
officer recognized him.
   The District Court in Sligo ordered Carron extradited to
British-ruled Northern Ireland but gave him 15 days to appeal the
order. The court ordered that he remain in custody pending appeal.
   In Dublin, Haughey said Saturday that a British court's refusal
to free six Irishmen accused of IRA bombings showed the need for
restrictions on the extradition of terrorist suspects to Britain.
   Dublin inserted new conditions Dec. 1 for extradition to
Britain. The measures include the requirements that British
authorities produce evidence on warrants in all extradition cases,
and that the Irish attorney general approve all extraditions.
   Britain has a ``historic inability ... to comprehend Irish
feelings and sensitivities,'' Haughey said in a speech to the
annual conference of the governing Fianna Fail party.
   Britain long has criticized the Irish Republic's reluctance to
extradite suspects sought for trial in connection with Irish
Republican Army actions. The IRA is fighting to end British rule in
Northern Ireland and unite the Protestant-dominated province with
mainly Roman Catholic Ireland.
   Haughey said the need for restrictions was exemplified by the
case of six Irishmen sentenced to life in prison for IRA's bombings
of two Birmingham pubs in 1974 that killed 21 people.
   Britain's Court of Appeal upheld their convictions last month,
rejecting arguments that new evidence undermined the confessions
and forensic findings that sent them to prison.
   ``The wisdom of, and the necessity for, the effective safeguards
provided in our extradition legislation has been clearly
confirmed,'' Haughey said. ``These safeguards are now in place and
it is on the basis of these safeguards, or not at all, that
extradition will proceed.''
   Carron's case was not affected by the legislation because
warrants seeking his extradition were issued in November, before
introduction of the new regulations.
   Carron came to prominence in 1981 when he was the election
officer for Bobby Sands, who launched a seven-month IRA hunger
strike at Belfast's Maze Prison that year.
   Sands, who was elected to the British Parliament while behind
bars, and nine other IRA members starved themselves to death during
the protest over prison regulations. When Sands died, Carron won
his parliamentary seat.
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary, Northern Ireland's police force,
had been hunting Carron since he jumped bail in January 1986 on a
charge of possessing a soldier's rifle. He had been released on
bail to run as a Sinn Fein candidate in special elections to the
British Parliament.
   After being defeated in the election, Carron failed to report
back to jail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
