<FILEID>AP-NR-02-20-88 2014EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Haiti     02-20 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Leader Leaves Haiti</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ An opposition leader who led two
unsuccessful invasions during the Duvalier family dictatorship left
the country Saturday after spending six months holed up in an
embassy, said Haiti Radio Inter.
   Bernard Sansaricq, who was granted political asylum by the
Argentine Embassy after the Haitian government accused him of
urging peasants to revolt, boarded an Eastern Airlines flight bound
for Miami at 5 p.m., the independent radio station said.
   Sansaricq, head of the National Peoples Party, was driven to the
airport in an Argentine Embassy limousine, accompanied by four
carloads of Haitian soldiers, the radio said.
   President Leslie Manigat, in an address on state television
Friday night, promised safe conduct ``for all of those in political
asylum.''
   Sansaricq, in his mid-40s, was the only person known to have
been in political asylum in Haiti.
   He was accused Aug. 3 last year of attempting to provoke a
revolution in Jeremie, his hometown, on the tip of Haiti's
southwestern peninsula. After a shootout with soldiers, he and
several supporters fled into the surrounding hills and disappeared
for three weeks.
   The military claimed he arrived with a group of armed men and
distributed weapons to peasants in the town.
   Sansaricq denied the charges. Sansaricq said in a radio address
from the Argentine Embassy on Aug. 25 that he had been armed only
with a revolver, for which he claimed to have a license.
   He said he went to Jeremie to attend a trial of people accused
of taking part in a massacre in 1964. Sansaricq said hundreds of
upper class mulatto families and suspected opponents of dictator
Francois Duvalier were massacred by soldiers and the Tontons
Macoutes, Duvalier's secret police.
   The government has never acknowledged the killings.
   Sansaricq, whose entire family was slain in the massacre, said
the army wanted to kill him since his testimony would have
implicated high ranking officers, including Defense Minister
Williams Regala, a reserve army brigidier general and former member
of the military-run junta.
   Sansaricq, who at one time owned a gas station in south Florida,
led foiled invasions in 1963 and 1982 during the 29-year
dictatorship of Francois Duvalier and his son, Jean Claude. He
lived in Miami from the early 1960s until 1986, when Jean-Claude
Duvalier fled into exile in France.
   The 1963 invasion occurred in Jeremie. He escaped, but 12
colleagues were captured and shot by a military firing squad. In
1982, he landed on the island of La Tortue on Haiti's northern
coast. Eight people died in the 1982 invasion and Sansaricq and
others were rescued by the U.S. Coast Guard.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
