<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Kenya-Elections     02-20 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kenya-Elections,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mob Stones Candidate, Other Candidate Claims He Was Kidnapped</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mob stoned one candidate's car, leaving
four injured, and at least one candidate was arrested for bad debts
as hundreds of political hopefuls registered for next month's
parliamentary elections.
   Daily Nation, an independent Nairobi newspaper, said supporters
of an opponent hurled stones Friday at the motorcade of Nahashon
Njuno, an assistant minister for tourism and wildlife in the
outgoing government.
   The attack took place at Kirinyaga, in central Kenya, where
Njuno was presenting papers qualifying him to stand in the March 21
elections.
   Njiru was among nearly 750 candidates who presented election
papers Friday at administration centers across the country.
   Candidates are contesting 188 Parliamentary seats. There are 202
seats in the Kenyan Parliament. Twelve members of Parliament are
nominated by the president.
   Kenya is a one-party state and all candidates must be approved
by President Daniel Arap Moi's ruling Kenya African National Union.
   In the western town of Nakuru, police arrested John Njenga
Mungai for failure to pay a $42 debt as he was about to present his
papers, according to another independent newspaper, The Standard.
   Mungai paid the money he owed the Ministry of Information and
Broadcasting for advertisements on state-owned television, the
newspaper said.
   The ruling Kenya African National Union disqualifies anyone
owing the government money from contesting.
   William Odongo Omamo, minister for research, science and
technology in the outgoing government, failed to get clearance to
run for election because officials said he had not paid a $1.1
million debt owed to the government.
   Daily Nation also reported that the High Court on Friday issued
a warrant for the arrest of candidate James Muriuki, a member of
Parliament in the 1970s, for not paying $4,640 in rent on a Nairobi
house as ordered by the court in 1983.
   Abisai Masinde, candidate for western Emuhaya constituency said
he nearly did not make it to present his election papers because he
was kidnapped.
   Masinde told The Standard, another independent newspaper, that
he was forced into the back seat of a car Thursday morning when he
was shopping at a market in western Kakamega.
   The kidnappers drove around with him until Friday afternoon,
when they released him without giving a reason for holding him,
Masinde said.
</TEXT>
