<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0620,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow And Cold Return To Great Lakes, Rain In Southeast</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT that time in Sault Ste. Marie was
EST, sted CST.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Frigid air slid across the Great Lakes and into the Midwest on
Saturday and made temperatures fall rapidly, and rain fell over
sections of the Southeast, pushing some streams close to flood
stage.
   The temperature at Sault Ste. Marie, Mich., crashed from a mild
30 degrees with light wind at around 5 a.m. to 16 degrees at 7 a.m.
EST, with strong northerly wind and half-mile visibility in blowing
snow. By 11 a.m., it was one degree above zero with a wind chill of
30 to 40 degrees below zero.
   By afternoon, snow and falling temperatures were common
throughout Michigan and snowdrifts blocked some highways on the
Upper Peninsula. The temperature at Lansing dropped 9 degrees in 15
minutes.
   The cold front moved through the Chicago area and roads were
iced by one to 4 inches of snow. Visibility dropped to around a
quarter of a mile in snow and blowing snow in northern Indiana.
   In the Southeast, rain was widespread from the eastern Carolinas
across southern Georgia and northern Florida to the southeast tip
of Louisiana. Cecil Field Naval Air Station at Jacksonville, Fla.,
measured 1.25 inches of rain in the six hours up to 1 p.m. EST.
   A flood warning was issued for the Satilla River in southeastern
Georgia and other rivers in northern Florida and southern Georgia
were swollen to near flood stage, with more rain expected, the
National Weather Service said.
   In Maine, moderate to heavy rain fell at Eastport while to the
north at Caribou it was cold enough for 3 inches of snow to fall in
the morning, bringing the city's total snow depth to 30 inches.
   Elsewhere, light snow fell across sections of the northern and
central Plains during the morning with an inch of snow at both
Grand Island, Neb., and Rapid City, S.D.
   High wind blew across parts of Colorado with gusts to 61 mph
recorded at Boulder. A high wind warning was issued for areas along
the eastern slopes of the Montana Rockies with gusts to 70 mph
possible.
   Florida also was a study in sharp temperature contrasts. At 2
p.m., Miami had a record 86 and Daytona Beach was a toasty 85, also
a record. But at the same time at Jacksonville, 90 miles north of
Daytona Beach, it was rainy and 57 degrees.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 5
degrees below zero at Warroad, Minn., to 88 at Orlando, Fla. The
low for the day was 22 degrees below zero at Warroad.
   For Sunday, rain was forecast over much of Florida with
scattered thunderstorms in the southern part of the peninsula. Snow
showers were forecast in northern Maine. Snow or snow showers also
were forecast from northern West Virginia to western New York and
from Michigan across Wisconsin and Minnesota to eastern North
Dakota.
   Highs in the teens or 20s were predicted from northern New
England across the Great Lakes and the Ohio Valley to the upper
Mississippi Valley; in the 30s or 40s from southern New England
across the mid-Atlantic states, the Carolinas, the Tennessee
Valley, the middle and lower Mississippi Valley and the Missouri
Valley to the eastern Dakotas; and over inland parts of the
Northwest; in the 70s in coastal and southern California, southern
Arizona and the southern tip of Texas; in the 70s to low 80s in
southern Florida; and in the 50s or 60s in most of the rest of the
nation.
</TEXT>
