<HEAD>Jury Finds Teen Guilty in Murder Retrial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to CORRECT that court involved in case was state
Supreme Court, sted federal. SUBS 8th graf, `The Supreme...', to
add `state.'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MARION, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black teen-ager sent to death row at age
15 was convicted Saturday of murder in a retrial brought after the
state Supreme Court overturned his original conviction by an
all-white jury. The prosecutor said he would not seek the death
penalty again.
   Ronald Ward, 18, showed no emotion and even smiled faintly at
the jurors as they filed out of the courtroom.
   The Crittenden County Circuit Court jury deliberated nearly 13
hours over two days before finding him guilty in the 1985 deaths of
three whites.
   Though he was convicted of capital murder, Prosecuting Attorney
Scott Hunter said he would not ask the jury to impose the death
penalty. As a result, Ward was automatically given life in prison
without parole, the only other possible sentence for capital felony
murder.
   ``The fact that he has been on death row for 2{ years was a
factor in the decision,'' Hunter said.
   He also said he considered the length of time the jury spent in
deliberations. ``I felt like I could not call upon this jury to do
more than they've done.''
   Ward's attorneys, Samuel Turner Jr. of West Memphis and Joseph
B. Brown Jr. of Memphis, Tenn., said a notice of appeal would be
filed immediately. The attorneys maintain that Ward was illegally
fingerprinted before his arrest.
   The state Supreme Court overturned the original conviction last
year, noting that an all-white jury convicted the 15-year-old black
boy of killing the three whites.
   The retrial jury had eight whites and four blacks.
   Ward was convicted of killing Lois Jarvis, 76; Audrey Townsend,
72; and a seventh-grade classmate of Ward's, 12-year-old Chris
Simmons, who was the grandnephew of the two women.
</TEXT>
