<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-Construction     02-20 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Construction,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan-U.S. Talks End Without Agreement On Construction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAORI KITAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese and U.S. officials failed to reach
agreement on opening some Japanese construction projects to
American firms, U.S. officials said Saturday.
   Japan recently offered to allow foreign participation in six
large public works projects, but U.S. officials said Saturday the
proposals were not enough. The officials held an unusual weekend
news conference at the U.S. Embassy, but spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Michael Farren, deputy undersecretary of commerce for
international trade, is heading the U.S. delegation.
   The six projects are expansion of the Tokyo International
Airport at Haneda, construction of a new airport in Hiroshima, a
bridge across the Akashi strait near Osaka, a highway along Ise
Bay, the development of a coastal area along the Tokyo Bay and work
at Osaka Port.
   ``A great many American firms have expressed tremendous interest
in gaining access to Japanese markets,'' said one official. ``But
the kind of things we called for in the way of construction
services on this list would only open door to a very narrow range
of American construction firms.
   ``We've come to a judgement that the list (of the six projects)
is not sufficient'' he said.
   The officials said the talks will probably continue in
Washington, where Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita met with U.S.
leaders on an official visit last month.
   Access to the Japanese construction market has been a major
trade issue in recent years between the two countries.
   Japanese companies won about $2.3 billion in contracts in the
United States in 1986, while U.S. firms did about $500 million in
business in Japan, according to construction officials.
   Japan has opened only two semi-public projects to U.S. builders
_ the Tokyo Bay bridge and the multi-billion dollar Kansai
International Airport project.
   The U.S. Congress last year passed legislation prohibiting
foreign companies from taking part in U.S. public works projects
for one year if their countries bar participation of U.S. firms in
their public works projects.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
