<HEAD>Gephardt Ads Draw Ire of Dukakis Supporters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIOUX FALLS, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis Saturday accused Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt of
running a television advertisement that distorts the governor's
views on agriculture.
   The ad, which first aired across the state Friday night, said
Dukakis would not take a stand on a family farm bill sponsored by
Gephardt and ended with a barb at Dukakis' much-criticized
suggestion that Iowa farmers consider raising Belgian endive, a
salad green.
   At a news conference, Minnesota Agriculture Commissioner Jim
Nichols, who supports Dukakis for the Democratic nomination for
president, said the governor's farm plan would work well for
Midwestern states.
   Although Dukakis praised Massachussetts farmers's efforts to
diversify by raising endive, he recognizes that nationally, ``we
need a fair price in the marketplace, and supply management,''
Nichols said.
   But after the news conference, Gephardt's South Dakota campaign
issued a statement contending Dukakis ``has repeatedly denounced
supply management for farmers.'' The statement included a Boston
Globe article quoting the governor as saying that controlling
production would be ``incredibly complicated and very
bureaucratic.''
   But, state Rep. Robert Duxbury of Wessington, a state
co-chairman for the Dukakis campaign, said,``Mike Dukakis has laid
out a very thoughtful agriculture policy for family farmers and
ranchers. He favors credit relief, supply management and fair
market prices for farmers.''
   State Sen. Roger McKellips of Alcester, another state
co-chairman, called the ads ``a new low in South Dakota
presidential politics'' and urged their removal.
