<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DonorBabies 1stLd-Writethru a0656 02-20 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Donor Babies, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0656,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baby Pulled Off Life-Support; Second Child Flown To California</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with quotes, background, criticism of
procedure; No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOMA LINDA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A brain-dead baby whose body was kept
alive in hopes of tranplanting his organs was removed from
life-support machines Saturday after no suitable recipient could be
found, officials said.
   Meanwhile, a child born Saturday with the same fatal defect in
San Antonio, Texas, was placed on a respirator and flown to
California to be enrolled in Loma Linda University Medical Center's
donor program.
   The babies were born without most of their brain and skull, a
fatal condition known as anencephaly.
   The child known as Baby John was born Tuesday and declared
brain-dead Thursday at Loma Linda. Officials had hoped to keep the
baby's body on life-support machines for up to seven days, hospital
spokeswoman Anita Rockwell said.
   By Saturday, Ms. Rockwell said, ``Physicians of four waiting
liver recipients of Baby John's same blood type refused the liver
because of its progressive deterioration over the past 36 hours.
   ``Despite a worldwide search, no infant of the same blood type
needing a heart has been found.
   ``Out of respect for the brain-dead infant and with the consent
of his mother, Dr. Joyce Peabody removed the artificial life
support from Baby John and his cardiac activity ceased at 2:15
p.m.''
   Anencephaly is fatal, usually within days after birth. An
infant's healthy organs can only be transplanted if organ damage is
prevented by maintaining the infant on life-support from birth.
   The first anencephalic child considered by Loma Linda hospital
for the pioneering procedure was the child of Brenda and Michael
Winner of Arcadia, Calif. But the baby was stillborn on Dec. 22.
   The use of such infants as organ donors has raised controversial
ethical issues, and Loma Linda is the first hospital in the United
States to develop a medical protocol allowing such transplants.
   The National Right to Life Committee has denounced the procedure
and complained that doctors have failed to do enough to ensure that
organs weren't removed from live children.
   One of the hospital's 13 heart transplant patients under age 4
received the heart of an anencephalic baby earlier this year from a
donor child in Canada.
   If the Texas baby is declared dead within seven days, and one or
more of her organs successfully transplanted, it would be the first
time that the procedure has been tried using an anencephalic baby
born in the United States.
   The infant, 6-pound, 1-ounce Evelyn Keys was put on a chartered
plane in Texas en route to Loma Linda. She was born with only a
brain stem, said Robert McNaughton, Wilford Hall Medical Center
spokesman in San Antonio.
   Evelyn is the first child of Airman First Class Todd Keys, 21,
and his wife, Judy, 22.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
