<1ST_LINE>u p AM-BabbittRally     02-20 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Babbitt Rally,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Presidential Candidate Greets And Thanks His Supporters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BURT GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bruce Babbitt's last stop on his way home
from 18 months of campaigning for the Democratic presidential
nomination was to tell a cheering crowd at his national campaign
headquarters Saturday that it was good to be home.
   ``I got a call a week ago from a neighbor of mine who said,
`Bruce, you may be hot stuff out there in the rest of the United
States, running for president of the United States, debating on
television all the time, but you better get home because you're
fence is falling down and the dog is wreckin' my lawn,''' Babbitt
told about 1,000 of his supporters.
   Babbitt, the former governor of Arizona, officially dropped out
of the race Thursday after disappointing showings in the New
Hampshire primary and the Iowa Democratic caucuses.
   Babbitt said he and his wife, Hattie, were going to spend some
time getting reacquainted and re-establishing their roots in
Arizona.
   ``I want you to know one thing: wherever we go, our roots will
always be in Arizona, he said.''
   Babbitt said he would be jumping into the fray of the
gubernatorial recall election, but not as a candidate.
   ``I want to take the time in the next month or two to try and
get back into the swing of what it is that's going on here, to
rejoin our fight here in Arizona,'' he said.
   Babbitt, introduced to the crowd by acting Gov. Rose Mofford,
who has replaced impeached Gov. Evan Mecham, said, ``I'm going to
join you in whatever way I can to make sure the change is
permanent.''
   He said he has been asked about his future plans and that he
hasn't ruled out anything except running for governor of Arizona,
adding that there were plenty of good candidates.
   ``It's all of you that gave me this opportunity. It was a great
run. I hope that I come back having reflected the spirit of
Arizona, our traditions, honor, on all of us. I'm glad to be home.
Thanks very much,'' Babbitt said.
   Asked what he had learned from 18 months of campaigning, said:
``I think most of all, a tremendous sense of faith and confidence
in the future of America.
   ``It's an incredibly diverse country, full of people just
bursting with energy, with optimism, who are really thirsting for
some leadership.... 1988 is going to be important, because we will
have a transition, and we've somehow got to capture a spirit of
challenge, of truth-telling, of a kind of willingness to tell the
American people the truth and get this economy moving.''
</TEXT>
