<1ST_LINE>u i AM-OlympicsNewspage     02-20 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Olympics Newspage,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boitane Captures First U.S. Gold Medal; Flaim Gets Silver</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALGARY, Alberta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Figure skater Brian Boitano won the
United States' first gold medal of the Winter Olympics on Saturday,
beating Canadian world champion Brian Orser.
   Orser took the silver and Viktor Petrenko of the Soviet Union
was third for the bronze.
   Boitano's win gives the United States one gold; one silver, also
won Saturday; and one bronze as the Olympics ended its first week.
   Boitano, the 1986 world champion and a four-time American
titlist, took the long program with a sensational exhibition of
freestyle skating.
   The 24-year-old from Sunnyvale, Calif., who was fifth in the
1984 Olympics, depicted the various stages of a soldier's life to
music from the film ``Napoleon.''
   He successfully performed all eight triple jumps, including two
in combination, and drew a standing ovation from the sellout crowd
at the Olympic Saddledome.
   He also won over five of the nine judges, who gave him eight
marks of 5.9 and one perfect 6.0, from the Czechoslovakian judge
for artistic impression.
   Orser, 26, also came in second at the 1984 Winter Olympics in
Sarajevo, losing the gold to another American, Scott Hamilton.
   Earlier Saturday, speed skater Eric Flaim won the first silver
medal for the United States. Andre Hoffmann beat Flaim by .06
seconds, giving East Germany its second gold medal of the day and
leading another Soviet-bloc day at the Olympics.
   The only other U.S. medal was a bronze in pairs figure skating
won Tuesday night by Jill Watson and Peter Oppegard.
   The Soviets now have 14 medals, including five golds; and East
Germany has 10, including six golds.
</TEXT>
