<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-Fighting     02-20 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Fighting,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Announce First Transport Ban of Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas said Friday
they will shut down road and highway transport nationwide next week
as part of their protest against the government's election plans.
   The 24-hour transport ban, set to begin at 12:01 a.m. Monday, is
the first scheduled by the rebels this year. The announcement, made
on the rebels' clandestine Radio Venceremos, said the action was
part of the guerrilla campaign against legislative and municipal
elections scheduled for March 20.
   The traffic bans have been effective in the past, especially in
the war-torn east. Motorists stay off the roads, fearing reprisal
by the guerrillas.
   Also Friday, the armed forces said five guerrillas and two
soldiers died in combat near the town of La Laguna, 55 miles north
of the capital. Six government soldiers were wounded, they said.
   Radio Venceremos claimed guerrilla forces inflicted 23
casualties on government troops in Thursday's clash at La Laguna.
It did not distinguish between dead and wounded and did not report
rebel losses.
   In another attack, rebels assaulted the local Civil Defense
headquarters, the mayor's office and the telephone office in San
Jorge before dawn Friday, according to sources in the town 95 miles
southeast of San Salvador.
   The sources, reached by telephone, said five Civil Defense
militiamen were killed and two wounded. They had no information on
guerrilla casualties.
   The guerrillas caused extensive damage, according to the
sources, who spoke on condition of anoymity.
   Guerrillas of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front have
pursued a steady campaign of economic sabotage as part of their
8-year-old war against the U.S.-backed government.
   In addition to the regular declaration of traffic bans, the
campaign includes the blowing up of utility poles, attacks on power
stations and raids on farms and warehouses containing coffee,
cotton and sugar _ the country's main export crops.
   There were seven guerrilla-imposed transport strikes last year.
Three violators of the strike were killed, about 30 were wounded
and 160 vehicles were destroyed or damaged.
   The insurgents on Wednesday carried out their biggest attack of
the year, assaulting the base of the 6th infantry brigade and a
cotton cooperative in Usulutan, 70 miles east of the capital.
   The rebel radio said the assault marked the beginning of a
campaign designated ``armed struggle is the alternative to the new
electoral farce.''
   Leftist parties have not participated in elections held during
the war, saying that their candidates' safety could not be
guaranteed.
</TEXT>
