<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Thailand-Laos     02-20 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thailand-Laos,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Truce Begins In Disputed Border Area</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOLLY YONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thai and Laotian forces began a truce
in a disputed border area Friday, pulling back from the hilly
ground where hundreds of comrades had been killed since November,
Thai officers said.
   After the cease-fire began at 8 a.m., two parallel rows of Thai
and Laotian flags were planted to mark a zone two miles deep that
soldiers are forbidden to cross, said the army chief of staff, Gen.
Charuay Wongsayant.
   Military officials of both sides agreed to the cease-fire
Wednesday after two days of talks in Bangkok. The disputed area is
about 240 miles north of Bangkok between Thailand's northern
province of Phitsanulok and Sayaboury province in Laos.
   Col. Rithee Rungkaputi, chief of civilian affairs for the 3rd
Army Region, said a half-hour skirmish occurred on a contested hill
an hour before the truce began, with no casualties. He said it
there probably was a delay in commmunicating the cease-fire order.
   Rithee also reported a heavy artillery exchange and two ground
battles Wednesday and Thursday, while military teams from the two
countries were meeting in Bangkok.
   Foreign Minister Siddhi Savetsila of Thailand told reporters
Friday that Foreign Ministry officials had been sent to France
seeking help in resolving the problem. Both sides claim the area on
the basis of recognized maps and a 1907 French-Thai treaty.
   The official Laotian news agency KPL quoted Maj. Gen. Thonglay
Kommasith, deputy head of the army's general political department,
as saying the talks in Bangkok ``paved the way toward negotiations,
a diplomatic channel to solve the Lao-Thai border problem.''
   Thonglay participated in the Bangkok meeting. The dispatch said
he spoke at a news conference Thursday in Vientiane.
   The agreement calls for the governments to hold talks within 15
days after the truce begins to determine the frontier line.
</TEXT>
