<2ND_LINE>AM-Posner Sentence,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Multi-Millionaire's Tax Evasion Sentence Begins By Helping Needy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN WINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millionaire industrialist Victor Posner began
serving part of a sentence for tax evasion Friday by handing out
rolls at a soup kitchen.
   ``He's being introduced to everybody on a first-name basis,''
said Barbara Smith, spokeswoman for Camillus House, a shelter for
the needy.
   The 69-year-old Miami Beach tycoon, who declined requests for
interviews, was received ``in just the same way as any other person
who comes here to work as a volunteer, although I realize he's not
a volunteer,'' Ms. Smith said.
   U.S. District Judge Eugene Spellman last week sentenced Posner
to work 5,000 hours of community service over five years. He also
must pay $3 million to help the homeless and $4 million in back
taxes, penalties and interest.
   Posner had faced up to 40 years in prison after pleading no
contest last Sept. 29 to evading more than $1.2 million in federal
taxes by inflating the value of land he donated to a Bible college
as a tax exemption.
   Posner, whose net worth was estimated at $240 million in 1984 by
Forbes magazine, will work one day a week for the next eight weeks
at the downtown shelter.
   Posner, accompanied by his attorney, Edward Bennett Williams,
began his five-hour shift by taking a tour of the shelter and
meeting other workers.
   He worked at an entrance gate, admitting people to the cafeteria
and making sure it did not exceed its capacity of about 100.
   When several news photographers tried to take his picture,
Posner went inside to serve rolls to people coming through the food
line, which serves 700 to 900 needy people each day.
   Several of the men who went through the food line said they knew
about Posner's background and found him to be friendly.
   ``He shook hands with me. He's a very nice guy,'' said Brote
Harris. ``I said, `Come on, papa, shake my hand. I'd like to shake
a millionaire's hand.'''
   Posner, wearing a white shirt and clear plastic gloves, chatted
with other workers as he handed out rolls. The meal also included
hot chicken, string beans and rice.
</TEXT>
