<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Peace     02-20 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Peace,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaragua Proposes Canada, Europe Aid in Verifying Peace Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Central America, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaragua proposed Friday that Canada
and five Western European countries take part in efforts to verify
compliance with a Central American peace plan.
   Foreign Minister Miguel D'Escoto told a news conference that
foreign observers would form permanent mobile units in each of the
five countries covered by the peace plan.
   The mobile units, he said, would be in place for a year and be
allowed to make on-site inspections without prior notice to ensure
the countries were meeting terms of the agreement.
   D'Escoto suggested that representatives from Canada, Spain,
Italy, Sweden, Norway and West Germany be members of the
verification panel.
   The countries, he said, ``have shown their willingness to take
part in this type of activity in order to achieve and guarantee
peace in Central America.''
   The presidents of Nicaragua, Costa Rica, El Salvador, Honduras
and Guatemala signed the peace plan last Aug. 7.
   D'Escoto said he offered the proposal at a verification meeting
of the Central American foreign ministers Wednesday. The officials
met for 10 hours in San Salvador, the capital of El Salvador, but
failed to agree on ways to determine compliance with the peace plan.
   They called for further talks in Guatemala by March 15.
   The peace plan calls for cease-fire negotiations between
governments and insurgents in El Salvador, Guatemala and Nicaragua
as a first step toward democratic elections.
   It also calls for political amnesties and a ban on all outside
military assistance to rebel groups.
</TEXT>
