<HEAD>Kurdish Hunger Striker Reported Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DIYARBAKIR, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Kurdish inmate died Friday, 12 days
after he and 600 other prisoners began a hunger strike to protest
prison conditions, the independent Hurriyet news agency reported.
   It identified the inmate as Mehmet Emin Yavuz, who had been
sentenced to die for carrying out terrorist acts as a member of the
outlawed Kurdish Labor Party. His death sentence was awaiting
parliamentary approval.
   Yavuz died in a hospital in Diyarbakir military prison where he
was taken along with six other inmates after their health
deteriorated during the hunger strike that began Feb. 8, the agency
said.
   The semi-official Anatolia news agency reported later Friday
that the Diyarbakir inmates stopped the hunger strike hours after
Yavuz' death.
   The government announced Thursday that it agreed to improve
prison conditions. However, the inmates and several relatives
continued the hunger strike Friday, contending that conditions
remained unchanged, Hurriyet said.
   Most of the inmates belong to the Kurdish Labor Party, which
seeks to set up an independent Marxist state in parts of
southeastern Turkey.
