<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Salvador     02-20 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Salvador,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sepulveda Responds to Salvadoran Protest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER PICHARDINI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Bernardo Sepulveda denied in
a strongly worded protest note that Mexico allows its territory to
be used by leftist rebels to threaten the government of El Salvador.
   ``The government of Mexico in no case allows the use of Mexican
territory by the groups of the FMLN-FDR (Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front _ Democratic Revolutionary Front) to develop
activities that have repercussions and attempt against the
stability of the Salvadoran government,'' Sepulveda said in a note
to Foreign Minister Ricardo Acevedo Peralta of El Salvador.
   The note, released Thursday afternoon, was in response to a
protest note Acevedo Peralta sent to Mexico earlier in the week.
   The FMLN links five guerrilla groups that have been fighting El
Salvador's U.S.-supported government for the past eight years. The
FDR is its political ally.
   The groups' joint political-diplomatic commission maintains an
office in Mexico City, as does clandestine rebel Radio Venceremos.
   Sepulveda said the office is allowed because Mexican law
establishes ``protection for political exiles who enter national
territory and the constitution guarantees for all people who are in
the territory liberty of association, transit and expression of
ideas.''
   A Foreign Ministry source, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said Sepulveda decided to make his response public because the
Salvadoran government released its note to the press. ``That goes
out of normal diplomatic channels,'' the source said.
   Relations between Mexico and El Salvador were tense in the early
years of the Salvadoran civil war, especially after then-President
Jose Lopez Portillo recognized the rebels as a legitimate political
force in a joint Mexican-French declaration in 1981.
   The friction has eased during the administration of President
Miguel de la Madrid, who succeeded Lopez Portillo in December 1982.
   Mexico helped form the Contadora group seeking peace for Central
America in January 1983, along with Panama, Colombia and Venezuela.
</TEXT>
