<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Terrorists     02-20 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Terrorists,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hunger Striker, Two Other Defendants Acquitted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of four leaders of the extreme left group
Direct Action who have been refusing food for 81 days was acquitted
Friday night on charges of attempted murder.
   Nathalie Menigon and the other two defendants in the case, Regis
Schleicher and Jean-Francois Gailhac, were found innocent by the
special Assizes Court. The court, which has judges serving as the
jury, was established last year for terrorism cases.
   The three were accused in the January 1982 shooting of Alain
Carpentier, then a leader of a squatters movement in eastern Paris.
   Carpentier testified Friday that he did not know the three
defendants, and said police had tried to get him to say the Direct
Action members were his assailants.
   ``I don't understand what you want of them,'' Carpentier said.
``I'm the victim, and I can tell you they had nothing to do with
this affair.''
   Police investigators told the court they considered the
defendants suspects after questioning Carpentier's friends and
family.
   Prosecutor Daniel Barreyre said in his closing argument that the
shooting was part of Direct Action's effort to gain control of the
squatters movement. He asked for 15-year sentences for each of the
three defendants.
   Ms. Menigon and three other Direct Action leaders, Joelle
Aubron, Georges Cipriani and Jean-Marc Rouillan, have been on a
hunger strike since Dec. 1, demanding an end to their solitary
confinement. They are being fed intravenously against their will.
   All four were convicted Feb. 12 in a lower court of criminal
association and given 10-year sentences. Ms. Menigon was convicted
Wednesday, also in the special Assizes Court, of attempted murder
of two policemen.
   Authorities say all of Direct Action's leaders are now in prison.
   Several human rights groups have urged the government to meet
the hunger strikers' demands, but Justice Minister Albin Chalendon
said he will not yield to what he called blackmail.
</TEXT>
