<2ND_LINE>AM-Surrogate Mom,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negotiations Fail, Judge Sets Ground Rules In Baby M Hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of Baby M have failed to reach
an out-of-court settlement on surrogate mother Mary Beth
Whitehead-Gould's visitation rights, sending the matter back to
court, it was announced Friday.
   Superior Court Judge Birger M. Sween on Friday set a hearing for
March 28 to determine the terms under which Mrs. Beth
Whitehead-Gould may visit the child she bore under a $10,000
contract and lost in the landmark court battle.
   Mrs. Whitehead-Gould is allowed to visit the child for two hours
every Tuesday pending Sween's decision.
   The state Supreme Court on Feb. 3 banned surrogate motherhood
for pay, voided the $10,000 contract, and reinstated her right to
visit the baby, now legally called Melissa Stern.
   The court said a Superior Court judge must decide the conditions
for visitation if Mrs. Whitehead-Gould and the child's father,
William Stern, failed to reach an agreement.
   ``We did talk and it did not work. We cannot settle the case,''
said Gary N. Skoloff, an attorney for the Sterns. He declined to
disclose the positions of both sides.
   Mrs. Whitehead-Gould's attorney, Harold J. Cassidy, said in a
statement Friday night the Sterns had not negotiated with the
child's best interest in mind.
   ``It is in the best interest of Melissa that she have the
opportunity to know and love and respect her mother,'' he said.
``Until Mr. and Mrs. Stern learn to accept this simple fact, there
cannot be further discussions.''
   The Baby M case began when the Sterns signed a contract with
Mrs. Whitehead-Gould for her to be artificially inseminated with
Stern's sperm and bear them a child.
   After the child was born, Mrs. Whitehead-Gould decided she
couldn't give up the baby. The Sterns sued to get the child back.
   On March 31 Superior Court Judge Harvey R. Sorkow upheld the
contract, terminated Mrs. Whitehead-Gould's right to the baby,
awarded custody to the Sterns and let Stern's wife, Elizabeth,
adopt the baby.
   The Supreme Court, in its 7-0 ruling, overturned all but the
custody decision.
</TEXT>
