<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WorldBank     02-20 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-World Bank,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World Bank Announces $75 Billion General Capital Incease</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Bank, a major source of credit for
poor countries, late Friday announced a five-year general capital
increase.
   President Barber B. Conable said the capital increase of $74.8
billion will enable the bank to lend money to developing countries
at the rate of $20 billion a year by the early 1990s.
   The World Bank, owned by its 151 member countries, lent a record
$14.2 billion in the fiscal year ending last June.
   Agreement of the shareholding countries on the new capital opens
the way for ``stronger World Bank support for the developing
countries'' and demonstrates ``the confidence of our shareholder
governments in the Bank,'' said Conable.
   It was the bank's third general capital increase in its 44-year
history. Earlier general increases, in 1959 and 1980, approximately
doubled the authorized capital. The latest increase will raise the
bank's authorized capital to $171 billion.
   Each of the 151 member countries contributes capital in
proportion to its holding of shares, with the United States the
largest shareholder with about 20 percent.
   Only a small part of the capital is actually paid in cash.
Friday's announcement said this would be 3 percent, with the
remaining 97 percent to be on call if needed to secure World Bank
borrowings.
   The guarantees of participating governments enable the World
Bank to borrow money in private capital markets and to invest the
proceeds while waiting to disburse it to poor countries.
   Last September, the Bank sold a record $750 million offering of
10-year notes in the U.S. market at 9.91 percent after earlier
selling issues of World Bank dollar and yen bonds outside the
United States. It registered $1.1 billion profit in the year ending
last June 30.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
