<HEAD>Peruvian Rebels Kill 10 Soldiers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas attacked a convoy of
Peruvian troops in the Andes and killed 10 soldiers and two
civilians, Defense Minister Enrique Lopez said Friday.
   The assault Thursday near a road construction site on the
outskirts of Huancavelica, a state capital 155 miles southeast of
Lima, was the most devastating in a wave of attacks by Shining Path
guerrillas this month.
   ``A group of army personnel were the object of a cowardly attack
by delinquent subversives,'' the Joint Military Command said. Lopez
and the joint command declined to elaborate on how the rebels
mounted the raid.
   Lopez said the troops were traveling in civilian vehicles from
Huancavelica to the road construction site to provide protection to
government workers.
   The Mao-inspired Shining Path has been fighting for eight years
to topple the government and install a Marxist state.
   A year ago, the guerrillas exploded a mine near Huancavelica
that killed 10 soldiers and four civilians. One week ago, in a
nearly identical attack, rebels killed 10 soldiers and wounded 14.
   Since early February, leftist guerrillas have killed five
telephone company workers, bombed and derailed two ore trains and
bombed the office of Royal Dutch Shell and five other private
offices in Lima.
   Huancavelica, one of Peru's most impoverished and isolated
regions, is under a state of emergency to counter rising guerrilla
violence.
   The government says more than 10,000 people, including troops,
police, guerrillas and non-combatants, have died during the Shining
Path insurgency.
</TEXT>
