<HEAD>Plane Crashes, Bursts Into Flame</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A twin-engine plane skimmed over rush-hour
traffic Friday and crashed on a freeway access road, killing all
three people aboard and spewing flaming debris that destroyed two
parked cars, authorities said.
   ``It looked like it was going to attempt maybe to come onto the
freeway, but as soon as it got over the freeway, it just
nosedived,'' said Victor Armendariz, who was at a stop light.
``There's not much left. It's just charcoal.''
   The Gulfstream Commander 680 went down in moderate snow and
light fog after takeoff from El Paso International Airport shortly
before 9 a.m., National Transportation Safety Board spokesman Tommy
McFall said.
   ``From the eyewitnesses we talked to, (the plane) didn't have
any power on the way down. It was silent,'' said police Sgt. John
Loy.
   The victims' identities were not immediately released. The
plane's destination was not available.
   The plane apparently developed landing-gear trouble and was
trying to return to the airport when it crashed onto the Interstate
10 access road, McFall said. The cause of the crash was under
investigation.
