<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Gelli     02-20 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Gelli,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gelli Refuses To Talk To Italian Investigators</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARMA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man known as the ``grand puppeteer'' for
his high-level personal connections dashed investigators' hopes
Friday that he would detail what he knew about the collapse of the
nation's largest private bank.
   Licio Gelli is accused in Italy of masterminding a group
involved in right-wing terrorism, subversion and spying. He was the
grandmaster of the P-2 (Propaganda Due) Masonic lodge, which
Italian officials linked to tax evasion, bribery, conspiracy to
topple the government and other spectacular crimes.
   But his extradition Wednesday from Switzerland came on grounds
he would only face charges of fraudulent bankruptcy in the 1982
collapse of Banco Ambrosiano.
   Gelli had written to magistrates in Milan and expressed his
willingness to discuss the collapse of the bank, but he refused to
talk to them when they visited him in jail in Parma Friday, said
officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   In 1981, Gelli fled Italy after police raided his office and
found a list of purported P-2 lodge members. The list included
Cabinet ministers, journalists, businessmen and generals. The
scandal toppled the government of Premier Arnaldo Forlani.
   Gelli was arrested in Switzerland in September 1982 when he
tried to withdraw funds from a frozen account at a Geneva bank. He
was sentenced to two months in jail for entering the country
illegally.
   In 1983, while awaiting extradition to Italy, Gelli escaped and
reportedly hid in South America for four years.
   He surrendered to Swiss authorities last September, reportedly
suffering from heart problems. He was convicted and sentenced to
two months in prison for paying a guard a $20,000 bribe to help him
escape.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
