<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Turkey-Emergency     02-20 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey-Emergency,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Turkey Recommends Extension of Emergency Rule To Nine Provinces</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government council recommended Friday
that emergency rule be extended in nine provinces to help combat
Kurdish insurgents, the semi-official Anatolia news agency said.
   The emergency rule would include Turkey's largest city,
Istanbul, and the southeast provinces of Bingol, Diyarbakir,
Elazig, Hakkari, Mardin, Siirt, Tunceli and Van, the news agency
said.
   The National Security Council, a powerful advisory body of
Cabinet members and top military commanders, announced its
recommendation after a meeting Friday, Anatolia said.
   Government troops and Kurdish guerrillas seeking autonomy have
fought since 1984. An estimated 10 million of Turkey's 52 million
people are ethnic Kurds and most live in the rugged terrain of east
and southeast Turkey.
   If the recommendation is approved by the one-house Parliament,
emergency rule in those provinces will be extended for four months
as of March 19, when a four-month period of emergency rule expires.
   Under emergency rule, civilian officials may impose curfews or
bar or censor a publication. It differs from martial law in that
emergency powers are assumed by civilian officials instead of
military commanders.
</TEXT>
