<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Economy,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gas Prices Raised 32 Percent To Help Pensioners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government raised gas prices
32 percent Friday in a new tax to help retirees, whose monthly
stipends have declined in value in the nation's economic crisis.
   President Raul Alfonsin and Congress proposed the gas tax last
month as a way to help finance a 40 percent increase in the monthly
pensions of retirees to 300 australs, or about $52.
   Economy Minister Juan V. Sourrouille said Friday inflation for
1988 was expected to exceed 100 percent. The inflation will come
despite the planned sale of some debt-ridden state companies and
programs to push export sales and increase income tax collections,
he said.
   Inflation stood at 175 percent last year, more than double the
82 percent rise in 1986. Blame was placed primarily on debilitating
strikes, low prices for exports and high losses from state-owned
companies.
   Last week, Argentina and the Scandanavian carrier SAS signed an
agreement in which SAS will buy 20 to 40 percent of state-owned
Aerolineas Argentinas, which is heavily in debt. Under the accord,
SAS has until May to determine its ownership share.
</TEXT>
