<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrugStudy-Fraud     02-20 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Study-Fraud,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Physician, Ex-Hospital Official, Charged In Drug Study Fraud</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A doctor and former hospital board chairman
was indicted Friday on charges he defrauded pharmaceutical
companies of nearly $2 million by falsifying test results on
experimental drugs.
   Dr. Robert A. Fogari, 46, of Saddle River, invented data and
patients, enrolled ineligible patients in the clinical studies and
failed to report adverse affects the drugs may have caused, federal
prosecutors said.
   The drugs tested were anti-inflammatory treatments for arthritis.
   One of the drugs was Feldene, a leading seller for the
pharmaceutical company Pfizer, which used Fogari's test results in
its advertising, said Assistant U.S. Attorney Paul Weissman.
   Fogari, who has a practice in Jersey City, also was charged with
obstruction of justice for allegedly inducing witnesses to lie to
investigators and a grand jury.
   He was accused of defrauding the companies, including Johnson &
Johnson, Pfizer, Upjohn and Warner-Lambert, from 1977 to 1985, when
the Food and Drug Administration barred him from performing trials.
   For part of that period, Fogari was chairman of the board of
managers of Jersey City Medical Center, where he was a board member
until last year. He also was chief of rheumatology at that hospital
and president of the medical staff at St. Francis Hospital in
Jersey City, U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito Jr. said.
   Pharmaceutical companies use doctors to perform clinical trials
and pay them on the basis of the number of patients and office
visits and the procedures performed.
   Fogari did not return a telephone call to his office. His
attorney, A. Patrick Nucciarone, said in a statement he is
convinced his client will be exonerated.
   Experimental drugs cannot be sold in the United States unless
approved by the FDA, which reviews clinical data provided by the
company before allowing their sale.
   Pharmaceutical companies provide the drugs free to physicians
conducting the clinical trials. The doctors in turn are required to
follow study guidelines, keep accurate records and provide them to
the FDA for review.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
