<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia-Corruption,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Booted Out of Party; Details To Be Published Later</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials involved in a widely
publicized bribery and corruption case tried in Slovakia have been
expelled from the Communist Party, the ruling Politburo announced
Friday.
   An announcement by the state news agency CTK said the presidium
also chided legal and judicial organs in the republic of Slovakia
for a slow approach to the case, which was reported in the West and
in Czechoslovakia's state-run media.
   The trial focused on Stanislav Babinsky, former head of a
catering and supply enterprise in Dolni Kubin in western Slovakia.
He was sentenced last summer to 14{ years in jail on charges he
misappropriated $382,000 in state property.
   Babinsky and his associates were accused of paying bribes,
giving away art work and antique furniture and arranging sex
parties in order to attract development aid to Dolni Kubin, a
mountainous agricultural region near the Polish border.
   There were persistent but unconfirmed reports that high
government and party officials were involved in the scandal.
   Friday's statement from the Communist Party's ruling presidium,
or Politburo, said functionaries had been expelled from the party,
while other unspecified ``comrades were accused falsely'' in
connection with the case.
   ``Every inconsistency or regard for the position of individuals
or even attempts to shield functionaries or leading workers ...
create distrust in the party,'' the statement said.
   Communist Party leader Milos Jakes stressed when he took over
the party leadership from President Gustav Husak in December that
corruption in official ranks must be combated.
</TEXT>
