<FILEID>AP-NR-02-20-88 0639EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-EconomyRdp     02-20 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Defends Economic Policy; Stock Market Hits Six-Week High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan contends in his annual economic report to
Congress that his tax and budget policies helped turn economic
despair into hope during his administration.
   The report issued Friday also downplayed problems associated
with the $2.4 trillion national debt and record trade imbalances
during the Reagan years.
   Separately, on Wall Street the Dow Jones industrial average
finished at a six-week high, rising 28.18 points to 2,014.59. The
widely-followed indicator had not closed at such heights since it
stood at 2,051.89 on Jan. 7.
   Market watchers attributed the rally to an increasingly
optimistic market outlook, due partly to signs of strength in the
manufacturing sector of the economy.
   In an eight-page introduction to this year's economic report,
President Reagan said the country was in much better shape than
when he took office seven years ago. The president said the
attitude toward the economy had shifted to hope from the despair
that prevailed in the early 1980s.
   ``The past five years of sustained and vigorous growth in
production, income and employment did not occur by accident,'' the
report stated. ``They were shaped by government policies explicitly
directed toward fostering the inherent dynamism of the private
sector.''
   During a separate press briefing, Beryl Sprinkel, the
president's chief economic adviser, said the United States had
produced 2{ times the number of jobs as the other top six
industrialized countries combined since the end of the 1981-82
recession.
   Addressing the nation's $400 billion foreign debt, Sprinkel
noted that the net payments to foreigners needed to service the
country's foreign debt represented just 0.1 percent of the $4.6
trillion U.S. economy.
   Sprinkel predicted an improving trade deficit would provide
about half of the country's overall economic growth this year,
which the administration is forecasting will slow to a 2.4 percent
from 3.8 percent in 1987.
   Sprinkel also said recent signs of economic slowdown did not
point to a recession in 1988. He said the recent string of three
consecutive declines in the Index of Leading Indicators signaled
slower economic growth in the first half of 1988 but not a
recession this year.
   Sprinkel discounted recent big declines in the key housing
construction sector during December and January, attributing them
to a too-restrictive monetary policy pursued by the Federal Reserve
in the months before the October stock market collapse.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880220-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-20-88 0640EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-Gillette     02-20 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gillette,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gillette To Resist Board Challenge By Coniston</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL MENEZES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In facing a proxy fight over four seats on its
board of directors, Gillette Co. might also be facing a referendum
on its future as an independent company, analysts say.
   Gillette said Friday it would resist an attempt by Coniston
Partners to place four representatives on board seats up for
election at the company's annual meeting in April, including the
seat of chairman Colman M. Mockler Jr.
   Coniston, which holds a roughly 6 percent stake in the giant
personal products maker, is attempting to pressure Gillette into a
restructuring or merger that would boost its share price.
   Gillette rose 25 cents to $38.87{ a share in New York Stock
Exchange trading Friday.
   Coniston pursued a similar strategy last year in leading the
successful campaign to break up Allegis Corp., leading analysts to
predict the battle over Gillette would be long and bitter.
   ``Coniston I don't think is going to go away any time soon,''
said Deepak Rap, who follows Gillette for the investment firm
Merrill Lynch & Co.
   Mockler, who also is Gillette's chief executive and president,
said Gillette would continue resisting Coniston in the belief that
the company would function best as an independent business.
   Gillette cited its 1987 financial results, which reflected a 12
percent rise in sales and a doubling of operating profit, indicated
that its business strategy was working.
   Andrew Shore, of the investment firm Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc., said proxy fights were difficult to win, but in this case
Gillette management would have its hands full.
   The company has rebuffed several buyout offers from Revlon Group
Inc. dating back to 1986. The latest _ a $47-a-share, or $5.4
billion, offer _ was spurned late last year.
   In addition, a major restructuring that it undertook after
turning down a $4.12 billion Revlon buyout offer in November 1986
may not have boosted Gillette's share price enough to suit major
investors who remain wary about the strength of the stock market in
the wake of October's crash.
   Gillette's recent stock price in the high-$30 range is well
below the high-$40 to low-$50 range analysts estimate is the
company's acquisition value.
   ``It's really a referendum, like a vote for Coniston is a vote
for the sale of Gillette,'' said Shore. ``That's going to be very
difficult for shareholders to turn down.''
   Revlon must have Gillette's consent to launch a takeover of the
company under terms of a 10-year standstill agreement it signed in
November 1986, when Gillette bought out Revlon's nearly 14 percent
stake in the company after spurning the $4.12 billion offer.
   Nevertheless, Revlon chairman Ronald O. Perelman reportedly
remains interested in acquiring Gillette.
   Shore said that in addition to opposing Coniston's slate of
directors, Gillette could take other defensive measures including
the issuance of more stock, a leveraged buyout, a recapitalization
or a ``white knight'' merger with a friendly suitor.
   Even its candidates win election, Coniston would be unable to
take control of Gillette's board because only a third of the seats
are up for election in any year. But analysts say a Coniston
victory could pressure the board to consider a merger.
   Keith Gollust, a principal in the partnership, contended the
proxy fight was mandated by Gillette's takeover defenses, which
essentially gave its board unilateral power to accept or reject any
merger offers.
